<HTML> <HEAD>

<title>City Farmer: City Farms Britain</title> </HEAD>


<BODY BACKGROUND="blue_background.GIF">

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<DIV ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="Britain"><IMG SRC="CityFarmerBanner.GIF"
ALT="GFUAbanner" ALIGN=middle WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="30"></A> <BR>

<H5><FONT COLOR="Navy">Published by City Farmer, Canada's Office of
Urban Agriculture</FONT></H5></DIV>

<P><BR>

<DIV ALIGN=LEFT><H1><FONT COLOR="RED">City Farms in the United
Kingdom</FONT></H1></DIV>

<PRE>  </PRE>

<CENTER> <IMG ALIGN=bottom WIDTH="248" HEIGHT="251" SRC="CityFarm.GIF"
ALT="City Farms"> </CENTER> <P>


<PRE>  </PRE>

<TT>(C) Copyright: City Farmer 1995</TT>

<P> In Vancouver, as in most cities in North America, farm animals are
outlawed by city bylaws.  But at <B>City Farm Byker</B>, a not for
profit centre in the heart of <B>Newcastle upon Tyne in England</B>,
they don't hide their animals. "We've got cows, goats, sheep, pigs,
donkeys, poultry and small animals like rabbits. Things you can do here
include: daily feeding and mucking out, milking and cheese making,
beekeeping and general animal care. There is also a riding stable with
horses and ponies close by the main Farm site, where volunteers can help
out."

<P> In Britain there are over 60 such City Farms linked to the<BR> <A
HREF="http://alice.cs.bris.ac.uk/SBLN/wwwuk/fedfarm/homepa.htm"><FONT
SIZE=4><B>National Federation of City Farms</B></FONT></A> <BR> The
Greenhouse<BR> Hereford Street, Bedminster<BR> Bristol BS3 4NA<BR>
Phone: 0117 923 1800 <BR> Fax: 0117 923 1900<BR>E-mail:
102404.14@compuserve.com




<PRE>  </PRE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Inner city children are able to learn at first hand how to
look after animals and plants, and how farming produces food for the
table. For many who never see 'real' countryside, this is there only
opportunity for contact with non-domestic animals.</BLOCKQUOTE>


<CENTER> <IMG SRC="angus.GIF" ALT="Huxley and Angus" WIDTH="306"
HEIGHT="182"> </CENTER><P>


<CENTER><TT>Photo of Huxley, a Vietnamese pot bellied pig<BR> and
Angus, volunteer at City Farm Byker</TT></CENTER>

<PRE>  </PRE>

<P> <CENTER><B>Byker Farm Is The Best</B><BR><BR>  <ADDRESS>by Amy and
Jenifer (Aged 10)</ADDRESS> <BR> All Animals are nice.<BR> Need all the
money they can get for food.<BR> In the farm we have ducks.<BR> My
favourites are the goats and cows.<BR> Around the farm we go.<BR> Let
people stroke animals.<BR> Some of the animals are cute.<BR> On the farm
we have pigs.<BR> No one is allowed in the River.<BR> The geese may
bite.<BR> Huxley eats lots and lots of food.<BR> Eat your sweets or
Huxley will.<BR> From the farm we get eggs and milk.<BR> Animals eat
grass and hay.<BR> Riding on horses here we go.<BR></CENTER>

<P> <BLOCKQUOTE>City Farms are also community gardens, providing space
for people to grow vegetables and flowers. At Byker Farm in Newcastle,
practical organic gardening courses are offered to the
public.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B>City Farm Byker<BR> Stepney Bank<BR> Newcastle NE1 2PW</B><BR> Phone:
232-3698 <P>

<P>

<H3>City Farms Site Now On The Web</H3>

<A HREF="http://www.demon.co.uk/london-calling/farm1.html"><FONT
SIZE=4><B>Surrey Docks Farm</B></FONT></A> is an inner city farming
project situated in 2.2 acres of land adjacent to the Thames in south
east London. The farm provides a context for community, environmental
and educational activities throughout the year. <P> The farm is open to
the whole community and is a lively place where people have the chance
to contribute to the farm's production in a practical way. Farm visitors
can see the gardens and dairy and buy fresh farm produce grown or
processed by students on the projects.

<PRE>  </PRE>

<A HREF="http://www.shef.ac.uk/city/charity/heeley/"><FONT
SIZE=4><B>Heeley City Farm</B></FONT> </A>Visit four acres of farm and
gardens just one mile from the centre of Sheffield. See rare and unusual
domestic animals including Ben and Smokey the Vietnamese pot bellied
pigs, Fern Chough the Exmoor pony and Molly the Irish moiled cow. Relax
in our healthy Caf&eacute; and Plant Centre. Play in our under 7's play
area (if you're young enough) or wander around our herb gardens,
polytunnels and vegetable plots.

<P><BR><BR>

