<HTML> <HEAD>


<title>City Farmer: Australian City Farms</title></HEAD>


<BODY BACKGROUND="blue_background.GIF">

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<DIV ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="australia"><IMG SRC="CityFarmerBanner.GIF"
ALT="GFUAbanner"  ALIGN=middle></A> <BR>


<H5><FONT COLOR="Navy">Published by City Farmer, Canada's Office of
Urban Agriculture</FONT></H5></DIV>

<P><BR>




<DIV ALIGN=LEFT><H1><FONT COLOR="RED">Australian City Farms,<BR>
Community Gardens<BR> and Enterprise Centres <BR>Inventory 1996</FONT></H1></DIV>




<IMG BORDER=2 WIDTH="173" HEIGHT="219" HSPACE=12 VSPACE=6 ALIGN=left SRC="aussicow.GIF"
ALT="Graphic"> <P>





<B>Australian City Farms, Community Gardens, & Enterprise Centre
Inventory (1996)</B> <BR>Dr. Darren Phillips of Hobart, Tasmania has
written and produced this timely 64 page booklet on city farming
"down-under". Copies of the booklet can be obtained from: <BR>Darren P.
Phillips <BR>Symbioun Australia, <BR>2nd Floor, 158 Collins St.<BR>
Hobart, Tasmania 7000<BR> The cost is Australian $15 per copy, plus
postage and handling of $5 within Australia and $7 (Overseas surface
mail) (though this charge may be adjusted for posting multiple copies.)


<P> "This inventory currently lists over 40 centres for Australia, drawn
from all six States and the Australian Capital Territory, bar the
Northern Territory. Many other centres are believed to be in existence
or in very early formative stages of development. The centres listed
vary widely in size, number of active site users, focus and range of
activities undertaken, period of establishment, etc. They extend from
large, highly organised centres with government support (usually local
government), to the communal gardening efforts of small groups of people
or small demonstration sites, through to exciting new 'Community
Supported Agriculture' business ventures such as that undertaken by
Lismore Challenge City Farm. This extraordinary range, highlights the
fact that it is not so much the size of the centre but the 'principles'
and methods of resource management being practised on-site that matter,
and that food production systems if well designed and maintained can be
highly productive in both small and large areas."

<P>


<FONT SIZE=6><FONT color="#wwwff0">Network</FONT></FONT>

<P>

Just prior to publishing this first Inventory of Australian City Farms,
Community Gardens & Enterprise Centres, a number of people/organisations
with a strong commitment to these activities have come together to form
a network of such centres. The network is focused on providing
information support and assistance in whatever way it can for city
farming and community gardening activities for each State in Australia.

<P>

The Network's contacts for information support and exchange, by State,
are as follows:

