<HTML> <HEAD> <title>City Farmer:Compost Hotline</title> </HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="blue_background.GIF">

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<DIV ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="hotline"><IMG SRC="CityFarmerBanner.GIF"
ALT="GFUAbanner" ALIGN=middle WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="30"></A> <BR>


<H5><FONT COLOR="Navy">Published by City Farmer, Canada's Office of
Urban Agriculture</FONT></H5></DIV>

<P><BR>

<DIV ALIGN=LEFT><H1><FONT COLOR="RED">Hello Compost Hotline:<BR> Can You Compost
Captain Crunch?</FONT></H1></DIV>



<PRE>  </PRE>


<TT>(C) Copyright: City Farmer 1995</TT>



<P>


This is just one of the more bizarre questions Spring Gillard answers as the GVRD
Compost Hotline Operator. "My answer was, well, if you mean the cereal no, grains
can attract rodents. If you mean the man, no, because we don't recommend
composting meat - again because it will attract rodents with the smell as it
breaks down!"

<P>
"Probably the question most often asked", says Gillard is, 'I've got millions and
millions of flies, they fly into my mouth every time I open the lid, what do I
do?' The problem is usually that they're not burying their food scraps well
enough. So we go over the correct formula: alternate layers of brown and green
and whenever it's a food scrap layer, give it a sprinkling of dirt. And make sure
you mix it up at least once every two weeks with a pitch fork or compost
aerator."

<P>
"Lately, we've been getting a lot of calls about the <B>Earth Machine</B> as a lot of
municipalities are offering this bin through their compost bin distribution
program. People think it's an actual machine that you plug in and it compacts
your food for you or something! But it's just a plastic container, not much
bigger than a garbage can. In a way it's better than technological wizardry -
it's like magic. You put all this garbage in and a few months later out comes
this black gold - an incredibly rich, organic fertilizer for your garden or house
plants!"
<PRE>  </PRE>



<H3>Compost Hotline Hot Tips on Composting</H3>

<OL>

<LI>Start with a layer of straw or twiggy material on the bottom for good air
circulation.

<P>
<LI>Alternate 2 to 4 inch layers of green (grass, food scraps, garden waste) and
brown (straw, dry leaves, stripped up newspaper) materials. Store up leaves in
bags in the fall for a good brown supply.

<P>
<LI>Sprinkle every food scrap layer (uncooked fruit and vegetables, no meat, fish,
dairy, oils, grains) with a light covering of ordinary dirt. Keep a bucket handy
by your bin.
<P>

<LI> Always cap off food scrap layer with brown layer after dirt has been added.
This will smother fly eggs and smells.

<P>
<LI> Mix contents of bin at least once every two weeks with a pitch fork or compost
aerator.

</OL>

<PRE>  </PRE>



<H3>Six Most Asked Hotline Questions</H3>

<OL>

<LI> <B>Q:</B> I've got millions of flies, what do I do?

<P>
<B>A:</B>	Cover your food scraps with a light layer of dirt, then a layer (2 - 4
inches) of brown material (leaves, straw or stripped up newspaper) or a 2 to 3
inch layer of dirt only.
<P>

<LI><B>Q:</B> Nothing is happening in my bin, what do I do?

<P>
<B>A:</B>	Chances are the balance is off in the bin and you may need carbon material
(brown). Add more brown and mix thoroughly.

<P>
<LI><B>Q:</B> My bin smells, now what?

<P>
<B>A:</B>	Add some dirt, mix in some brown material, aerate (mix up), and then cap it
all off with a brown layer.

<P>
<LI>	<B>Q:</B> Where do I get worms and how do I start a worm bin?

<P>
<B>A:</B>	The hotline maintains a complete list of worm farmers and can tell you how
to set up a bin. Call the hotline for a worm supplier in your area.
<P>

<LI>	<B>Q:</B> Where can I get a compost bin?

<P>
<B>A:</B>	Call the hotline to see if your municipality is offering a bin distribution
program.
<P>

<LI>	<B>Q:</B> Where can I get rid of my heavier yard waste - shrub and tree trimmings,
etc.?

<P>
<B>A:</B>	Call the hotline for green waste sites in your area.

</OL>

<PRE>  </PRE>

If you have a question for the <B>Compost Hotline, call 736-2250</B>. It's a seven day
service - so even if you don't get a live operator, someone will get back to you
very quickly. Happy composting!

<PRE>  </PRE>

Go back to <A HREF="homecompost4.html#composting">Urban Home Composting</A> <P>




<P><BR><BR>

