<title>Urb Food Prod Food Cash</title> <H3>Urban
Agriculture Notes</H3> <H4>City Farmer: Canada's Office of Urban
Agriculture</H4>


<H3><hr><A NAME="luc cash"> URBAN FOOD PRODUCTION:<BR>
EVOLUTION, OFFICIAL SUPPORT AND SIGNIFICANCE<BR> (with special reference to
Africa)</H3> </A>

<H3>4.0	SIGNIFICANCE OF URBAN AGRICULTURE</H3>

<H3>4.6	City Farming's Benefits to Urban Households</H3>

<H2>4.6.3	Cash Savings</H2>


<ADDRESS> by Luc J.A. Mougeot <BR> &copy Copyright 1994<BR>
International Development Research Centre </ADDRESS>

<P>



In <B>Dar es Salaam</B>, the lower-income group spent 77% of its income on
purchasing food; home-cultivation supplied the equivalent of 37% of
their income and saved them 50% of their expenditure in food (Sanyal,
1986: 32). In <B>Addis Ababa</B>, cooperative households consumption of
vegetables was 10% higher than the urban average and this enabled
them to save 10 - 20% of their income (Egziabher, 1994). In <B>Maseru,
Lesotho</B>, a detailed survey of 428 plots revealed  that, in the late
1980s, 69%, 51% and 32% of low, medium and high-income vegetable
producers (respectively) were trying to save money through growing
vegetables at home; about 66% of the high-cost, and 29% of the
low-cost, district households claimed to sell some of their produce
regularly (Greenhow, 1994: 2).


<P>Go back to <A HREF="lucTOC26.html#luc TOC">Table of Contents:
Urban Food Production by Luc Mougeot </A>

