<title>Urb Food Prod Food Income</title> <H3>Urban Agriculture
Notes</H3> <H4>City Farmer: Canada's Office of Urban Agriculture</H4>


<H3><hr><A NAME="luc income"> URBAN FOOD PRODUCTION:<BR> EVOLUTION,
OFFICIAL SUPPORT AND SIGNIFICANCE<BR> (with special reference to
Africa)</H3> </A>

<H3>4.0	SIGNIFICANCE OF URBAN AGRICULTURE</H3>

<H3>4.6	City Farming's Benefits to Urban Households</H3>

<H2>4.6.4	Income Generation</H2>


<ADDRESS> by Luc J.A. Mougeot <BR> &copy Copyright 1994<BR>
International Development Research Centre </ADDRESS>

<P>

Urban agriculture can also increase a household's cash income. In
<B>Bolivia</B>, urban food projects supply women producers with 25%
of their total income (Prudencio, 1993: 15). In <B>Dar es Salaam</B>,
incomes obtained from UA are larger than regular salaries for 67% of
respondents (Sawio, 1993: 312). In <B>Addis Ababa</B>, all urban
cooperative farmers showed incomes well above those of half the
city's population: 50% earned more than 70% of the city's employed
population (Egziabher, 1994). In <B>Nairobi</B>, 47% of the urban
farmers had no visible means of support other than their urban shamba
plots (Freeman, 1991:135).


