<TITLE>Environmental Science Research</TITLE>
<meta name="resource-type"
value="document">
<meta name="distribution"
value="global">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<img src="/images/cpes.gif">
<H2>Environmental  Science</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
The School introduced an undergraduate degree programme in environmental
science in 1974.  Numbers have grown steadily and Sussex graduates
have achieved responsible positions in industry or public utilities.
Research in environmental science is now expanding.
<P>
<B>Dr M H Ford-Smith</B>
<P>
Chemical properties of clays and soils.
<P>
<A HREF="http://ahudson.mols.sussex.ac.uk/res.html" >Dr A Hudson</A>
<P>
Electron spin resonance of free radicals and photochemical systems.
 Applications to environmental problems.
<P>
<A HREF="/faculty/gjl/" >Professor G J Leigh</A>
<P>
Chemistry of coordinated dinitrogen.  Nitrogen-containing species
in the environment.
<P>
<B>Dr A S Potts,  Professor H M Rendell,  Dr D A Robinson,  Dr
R G B Williams</B>
<P>
<A HREF="http://geosun.geog.sussex.ac.uk/Geography/geog_faculty.html"> Geography Subject Group</A>
<P>
River geochemistry.  Hydrological aspects of flooding.  Effects
of soil erosion and mass movement.  Thermoluminescent techniques
for dating.  Soil chemistry.
<P>
<B>Dr G Taylor</B>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.biols.sussex.ac.uk/biols/Biology"> Biology Subject Group </A>
<P>
Effects of environmental change on plant growth. 
<P>
