<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Professor G. Jeffery Leigh</TITLE>
<meta name="resource-type" value="document">
<meta name="distribution" value="global">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/cpes.gif">
<H2>Professor G Jeffery Leigh</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR>

 E-Mail : <A HREF="MAILTO:g.j.leigh@sussex.ac.uk">G.J. Leigh@Sussex.ac.uk</A>
<P>
It is recognised that metalloenzymes are a ubiquitous group of materials involved in a wide range
of biological reactions. A principal interest is the conversions of small molecules and ions in the
nitrogen cycle, including N<SUB>2</SUB>, N0, N<SUB>2</SUB>0, N0<SUB>3</SUB>-,
 and N0<SUB>2</SUB>-. Many of these conversions are
mediated by metalloenzymes, but the detailed chemistry of reactions such as the conversion of N<SUB>2</SUB>
in to NH<SUB>3</SUB> (nitrogen fixation) aild the conversion of N0<SUB>2</SUB>- in to
 N<SUB>2</SUB>0 is not understood. We
therefore study model reactions of complexes containing the metal elements at the heart of the
relevant metalloenzymes, particularly Fe, V, and Cu. Thus we have shown how iron complexes
can mediate the conversion of N<SUB>2</SUB> in to NH<SUB>3</SUB>, and how 
N<SUB>2</SUB> bridging between vanadium atoms can
also produce ammonia. We wish to learn more about the function of N0 in biological systems, and
have investigated new methods for the oxidation of N<SUB>2</SUB> and the reduction of N0. Consequently we
are learning more about how these simple materials react, but we have also uncovered novel
aspects of coordination chemistry, such as a high-spin square-planar complex of iron(II) and
polymeric materials based upon vanadium-oxygen chains.
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="gjl.gif">
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
The stucture of the ion [{V(salen)3<SUB>4</SUB>(F-0)3]<SUP>2+</SUP><BR>
The angle V(l)-0(1)-V(2) is 162.2(1)&#176;. The ion
is centrosymmetric, and hence V(2)-0(2)-V(2')
must be 180&#176;
<P><H3>Selected Publications</H3><P>
A linear tetranuclear vanadium-oxygen assembly, <CITE>J Chem. Soc., Chem.
Commun.,</CITE> 1991, 827.<P>
Iron complexes with polythioether ligands: the relation of unusually large Mossbauer quadrupole
splittings to structure,<CITE> J Chem. Soc., Dalton Trans., </CITE>1992, 2033.<P>
Isolation and characterisation of iron(II) complexes with dinitrogen and of other derivatives,
especially from phenylacetylene,<CITE> J Chem. Soc., Dalton Trans</CITE>., 1993, 75.<P>
The protonation of bridging dinitrogen to yield ammonia, <CITE>J Chem. Soc., Chem. Commun.,</CITE> 1991,
921.<P>
Exchange of dinitrogen between iron and molybdenum centers and the reduction of dinitrogen
bound to iron: implications for the chemistry of nitrogenases,<CITE> J Am. Chem. Soc.</CITE>, 1991, 113, 5862.<P>
<P>
<A HREF=http:/faculty.html>Return to Faculty Index.
<IMG SRC="/images/mouse.gif" align="middle"></A>
</body>
