<HEAD>
<TITLE>Professor F Geoffrey N Cloke</TITLE>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="MOLS">
<META NAME="CREATIM" CONTENT="1995:6:8:9:21:">
<META NAME="VERSION" CONTENT="1">
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>

<TABLE BORDER=0 CELL PADDING=10>
<IMG SRC="/images/cpes.gif">
<H1>Professor F Geoffrey N Cloke</H1> 
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<B> E-mail  <A HREF="mailto:F.G.Cloke@Sussex.ac.uk" >F.G.Cloke@sussex.ac.uk
</A></B>
<P>
Our interests lie in the synthesis, reactivity, and electronic
structure of organometallic and coordination compounds of the
d-, f-, and p-block elements in novel oxidation states/ligand
environments.  One of our main synthetic strategies is the use
of metal vapour synthesis, e.g. in the preparation of (i) the
first zero oxidation state complexes of scandium, yttrium, and
the lanthanide elements (e.g. <B>1</B> and photograph), compounds
which are of fundamental interest in terms of their structure,
magnetic properties, and bonding, as well as being very active
homogeneous and heterogeneous olefin polymerisation catalysts;
(ii) new classes of organometallic sandwich compounds, such as
the bis(-butadiene)metal complexes <B>2</B>; and (iii) p-block
complexes, such as the first monomeric Al(II) complex <B>3</B>,
which also have potential application in chemical vapour deposition.
 In more &quot;conventional&quot; areas, we are exploring the
potential of the new ligand.
<P>
1,4-bis(trimethylsilyl)-cyclooctatetraene for the synthesis of
cationic early transition metal alkyl derivatives, e.g. <B>4</B>,
which are key intermediates in Ziegler-Natta catalysis.  Novel
early transition metal and f-element alkyls and hydrides, e.g.
<B>5</B> and <B>6</B>, are also being examined as homogeneous
catalysts for copolymerisation of polar olefins.  Most recently,
in collaboration with Dr G A Lawless, we have embarked on a programme
to study the interactions of highly Lewis acidic organometallic
complexes with small molecules (e.g<I>.</I> CH4, H2, N2) in supercritical
xenon solution by high-pressure NMR spectroscopy.
<BR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">

<IMG SRC="fgnc1.gif">

<IMG SRC="fgnc2.gif"> 
<BR>
<P>
<B>Selected Publications</B>
<P>
Zero oxidation state compounds of scandium, yttrium, and the lanthanides,
<I>Chem. Soc. Rev.</I>, 1993, <B>22</B>, 17.
<P>
Synthesis and reactivity of bis(-1,4-di-tert-butylbuta-1,3-diene)cobalt;
the X-ray crystal structure of the anionic butadiene sandwich
complex [K(18-crown-6)(thf)2][Co(-C4H4But2)2], <I>J. Chem. Soc.,
Chem. Commun.</I>, 1993, 248.
<P>
Butadiene 'sandwich compounds': synthesis of bis(-1,4-di-tert-butylbuta-1,3-diene)
complexes of titanium and vanadium, <I>J. Chem. Soc., Chem. Commun
</I>., 1991, 1470.
<P>
Paramagnetic aluminium-1,4-di-t-butyl-1,4-diazabutadiene (dbdab)
complexes derived from metal vapours and/or metal hydrides: crystal
structures of [Al(dbdab)2] and [Al(dbdab){N(But)CH2}2], <I>J.
Chem. Soc., Chem. Commun</I>., 1990, 1394.
<P>
Trimethylsilyl derivatives of cyclooctatetraene, <I>J. Organometal.
Chem</I>., 1993, <B>462</B>, 39. 
<P>
<A NAME="CE"></A>
