<TITLE>Dr. Peter Scott</TITLE>
<meta name="resource-type"
value="document">
<meta name="distribution"
value="global">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<img src="/images/cpes.gif">
<H2>Dr. Peter Scott</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=3>E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:p.scott@sussex.ac.uk"> P. Scott@sussex.ac.uk</A></FONT> 
<H3>Brief Career History</H3>
<UL><LI>First class B.Sc. (Hons.) in Applied Chemistry, University of Salford (1984 - 1988)
<LI>D. Phil. Balliol College and Inorganic Chemistry Laboratory, Oxford. (1988 - 1991)<BR> with
Malcolm L. H. Green. F. R. S.
<LI>Royal Society European Science exchange Fellow, Konstanz, Germany 1992 with H.-H. Brintzinger
<LI> British Ramsay Fellow (1993 -1995) and Lecturer in Chemistry.
</UL>
<P>
<H3>Research Programmes & Opportunities for Graduate Students</H3>
<H4><IMG SRC="/images/a15.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM>Synthesis of Chiral Catalysts for Enanitioselective Organic Transformations</H4>
Our aim is to discover novel and practical catalytic asymmetric reactions and to 
develop and understand them from the perspective of both the inorganic and organic chemist.
We are thus keen to hear from any potential graduate students who might otherwise find 
themselves bored in either single field and who would like to work in our multi - disciplinary group.
There is considerable potential for industrial support of our studentships. 
<P>
<H4><IMG SRC="/images/a15.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM>Coordination Chemistry of the Actinides</H4>
Our kind sponsor (BNFL) is happy to let us discover catalytic and other activity that may
lead to the peaceful uses of uranium metal. So far out work has encompassed polymer catalysis,
small-molecule activation and mixed-valence systems. In the process of our work we occasionally
stumble across some pretty awesome activity. This programme is hard but offers excellent
training for those interested in modern organometallic and coordination chemistry.
<P>
<H3>Grants for Research  & Industrial Support 1994 - date</H3>
<UL><LI>Royal Society Research Grant 1994
<LI> BNF Plc. CASE award 1994
<LI>Royal Society Research Grant 1995
<LI>Rhone - Poulenc Industrial CASE award 1995
<LI>University of Sussex Research Development Grant 1995
</UL>
<P>
<H3>Facilities</H3>
<STRONG><IMG SRC="/images/a15.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM>In the School</STRONG><P>The school (research rating: 5) has outstanding facilities including 
<UL><LI> NMR (500, two 400, 360 and 250Mhz)
<LI>Modern V.G. Autospec Mass Spectrometer
<LI>Diffractometers
<LI>ICP and HPLC
</UL>Just about anything you might want with most of it hands on.
<P>
<STRONG><IMG SRC="/images/a15.gif" ALIGN=BOTTOM>In the Group</STRONG><P>We are well equipped for both organic and inorganic chemistry 
using standard methods as well as Schlenk techniques using high quality vacuum lines and pumps.
We have a sophisticated MBraun inert atmosphere glove box, plug and play MacLab electrochemical 
apparatus, a polarimeter and a chiral gas chromatography set-up.  
<P>
<H3>Selected Publications</H3>
<P>
<UL><LI>Synthesis, Structure and Electrochemistry of a Paramagnetic 1,4-Diabutadiene Thorium Compex,
P. Scott and P. B. Hitchcock <CITE>J.Chem. Soc. Chem. Commun.,</CITE><STRONG1995,</STRONG>
579.
<LI> Synthesis, Structure and Electrochemistry of the First Fulvalene Deriivative of an Actinide,
P. Scott and P. B. Hitchcock,<CITE>J. Organomet. Chem.,</CITE><STRONG>1995</STRONG>
497, C1 (Hans Brintzinger 60th, Birthday Edition)
<LI>Exploring the Auxiliary Co-ordination Sphere of Tripodal Amino(triamido) Actinide Complexes
P. Scott and P. B. Hitchcock <CITE>J.Chem. Soc., Dalton Trans</CITE><STRONG>1995</STRONG>603
<LI>[(C_3Bu^t3)V(CO)4]; Partial insertion of Vanadium into the Cyclopropenyl Ring
R. B. Blunden, F. G. n. Cloke, P. B. Hitchcock and P. Scott,<CITE>Organometallics,</CITE><STRONG>
1994,</STRONG> 603.
</UL>
<hr>
