<HEAD>
<TITLE>Dr James R Hanson</TITLE>
<meta name="resource-type"
value="document">
<meta name="distribution"
value="global">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<img src="/images/cpes.gif">
<HR>
<H3>Dr James R Hanson</H3>
</CENTER>
<HR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:j.r.hanson@sussex.ac.uk">J. R. Hanson@Sussex.ac.uk</A>
<P>
Many fungi produce biologically-active metabolites, some of which are useful as, for example,
antibiotics, tumour-inhibitory substances, or plant-growth regulators. The biosynthetic
pathways
leading to these metabolites have been shown to have some substrate flexibility, allowing the
organism to bio-transform substances similar to their natural biosynthetic intermediates.
Information accrues from these biosynthetically directed transformations on the
stereo-electronic
requirements of specific enzymatic steps. However the rules that govern the extent of this substrate
flexibility are unknown. It is the object of our research to establish these in the context of the
biosynthesis of the tumour-inhibitor aphidicolin, the gibberellin plant growth regulators, and some
antibiotics from <I>Gliocladium</I> and <I>Penicillium</I> species. Current studies concern the overlap
between the regiospecificity of steroid hydroxylations and biosynthetic hydroxylations, the factors
that govern methyl group hydroxylations, and the use of biosynthetically-directed sesquiterpenoid
cyclisations.

There is currently interest in the chemical modification of the steroid hormones to produce
compounds that inhibit specific enzymes involved in prostate disease and breast cancer. In this
context research is in progress to introduce on to the steroid framework functionality associated
with the tumour inhibitory properties of aphidicolin and related diterpenoids. These synthetic
studies, particularly with conformationally rigid structures, also allow us to examine the stereo-
electronic features that govern various chemical reactions.
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="jrh2.gif">                  
<P>
        
<H3>Selected Publications</H3>

Microbiological transformation of diterpenoids,<CITE> Nat. Prod. Rep.,</CITE> 1992,<B> 9,</B> 139.

Biotransformation of steroids by C. aphidicola,<CITE> Phytochemistry</CITE>, 1993, <B>33,</B> 831.

Stereochemistry of the relationship between substrate and oxidant in the hydroxylation of
aphidicolin,<CITE> J. Chem. Soc., Perkin Trans. 1</CITE>, 1992,<B> 1,</B> 2079.

      
