<HTML>
<TITLE>Dr. Stephen Caddick</TITLE>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/cpes.gif">
<H1>Dr. Stephen Caddick</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR><P>
e-mail:- <A HREF="mailto:s.caddick@sussex.ac.uk">S.Caddick@sussex.ac.uk</A>
<P>
The majority of our research is directed towards the development of new methodologies fro the synthesis of target
compounds of biological interest, eg Vindoline (fig 1) and Neocarzinostatin (fig 2.).
<P>

<IMG SRC="cad1.gif" ALT="Vindoline">
<IMG SRC="cad2.gif" ALT="Neocarzinostatin">
<P>
(i)<STRONG>Synthesis of indoles and indole alkaloids</STRONG>
The indole nucleus is present in a wide range of biologically important pharmaceuticals and natural products.
 We aim to develop very general new approaches to functionalised indoles on which drug discovery programmes
 can be based. We have recently developed an exciting new methodology for the preparation of fused indole ring systems
and we are now using this approach for the synthesis of naturally occurring indole alkaloids, for
example Vindoline (fig1).

<P>

(ii) <STRONG> Design, synthesis and evaluation of enediyne anti-cancer antibiotics</STRONG>
The enediynes have
been the subject of extensive scientific investigations because of their potent anti-cancer activity.
Their mode of action is unusual and because of this, and their unique molecular architecture, these
materials have become attractive targets for bio-organic chemists. We have a programme directed
toward the synthesis of Neocarzinostatin Chromophore 2 and a range of structurally simple
analogues for biological evaluation; a long term aim is the development of new treatments for
cancer.
<P>
<STRONG>Other areas of current interest</STRONG>
Other areas of current interest We have a number of other current programmes including new
free radical based synthetic methodologies, microwave-mediated organic reactions, development of
novel insect anti-feedants, drug metabolism, and toxicology.
<P>
<A HREF="/resgrps/sjc/welcome.html"><STRONG>My research group's pages </A>
are here.</STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG>Selected Publications</STRONG>

1,5-Allylic abstraction, cyclisation: a new route to five-membered carbocycles, Tetrahedron Lett.,
1990, <STRONG>47, </STRONG>6911.
<P>
Approaches to bicyclic ring systems via 1,5-allylic abstraction, cyclisation, Tetrahedron, 1992, <STRONG>48</STRONG>,
10655.
<P>
A regioselective synthesis of heteroaromatic stannines via radical displacement of heteroaromatic
tosylates, Synlett., 1992, 805.
<P>
An intramolecular radical cyclisation approach to fused [1,2-a] indoles, Synlett., 1993, 23.
<P>
