<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Dr. Richard A. Jackson</TITLE>
<meta name="resource-type"
value="document">
<meta name="distribution"
value="global">
</head>


<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<img src="/images/cpes.gif">
<H1> Dr. Richard A. Jackson</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<B> E-mail  <A HREF="mailto:R.A.Jackson@sussex.ac.uk"
>R.A.Jackson@sussex.ac.uk</A></B>
<P>
A wide range of mechanistic and synthetic problems in free radical chemistry is being studied.
<P>
Organosilicon radicals show completely different reactivity from carbon-centred radicals:
addition takes place to the oxygen atom of the carbonyl group, and halogen atoms are extracted 
from organic halides. The differences can be utilized for example in a method of making specific
alkyl radicals from halides and in synthetic procedures for dehydroxylation  and decarboxylation.
<P>
Radical reactions on zeolites are being explored: the narrow channels constrain
organic molecules causing different positional selectivity that we intend to exploit
synthetically.
<P>
Substituents can stabilize or destabilize ions; most substituents stabilize radicals.
A new scale of substituent constants is needed, and we have suggested a Hammett-type scale
based on the decomposition of substituted dibenzylmercurials. EPR studies of substituted benzylic radicals also provide information about radical stabilization.
<P>
We have developed computer methods for the
objective analysis of complex EPR spectra, even for weak spectra where
individual lines are difficult to identify.  Stabilization effects in phenoxyl radicals have been 
studied and related to biological antioxidants such as Vitamin E. <I>Para</I>-substituted 2,6-di-<I>tert</I>-butylphenoxyl radicals are
also models for the active site in ribonucleotide reductase enzymes; we are investigating the
chemistry of such radicals with a view to discovering reductase inhibitors.
<P>
The (radical) reactions involved in the production and destruction of 
benzene in combustion of automobile fuels are being studied using deuterium-labelled hydrocarbons; mechanistic insight may 
lead to lower levels of emissions.
<P>
In collaboration with Dr Steve Armes we have just initiated a project on novel capping agents for living radical polymerisations.
 <P>
<STRONG>Selected Publications</STRONG>
<P>
Phenol/phenoxyl radial equilibria by electron spin resonance:
Are radicals derived from tocopherol and analogues especially stabilized?
<I> J. Chem. Soc., Chem. Commun.</I>, 1992, 967. (With M. K. Mousavi Hosseini.)
<P>
The Intermediacy of Free Aryl Radicals in the Reaction of <I>o</I>-Alkenyloxybenzenediazonium Salts with Ferrocene.  <I>Aust. J. Chem.</I>, 1992, <STRONG>45</STRONG>, 857.  (With A. L. J. Beckwith and R.W. Longmore.)
<P>
The Thermal Decomposition of Dibenzylmercury:
A Suitable Model Reaction for Determination of Substituent Effects on Radical Stability?
<I>J. Organometal. Chem.</I>, 1992, <STRONG>437</STRONG>, 77.
<P>
EPR Spectra of 3,5-Disubstituted Benzyl Radicals. 
<I>J. Chem Soc., Perkin Trans. 2</I>, 1992, 885. (With R. Moosavi.)
<P>
Electron Spin Resonance Spectra of Substituted 1- and 2-Naphthylmethyl Radicals. <I>J. Chem Soc., Perkin Trans. 2</I>, 1993, 53. (With C. J. Rhodes.)
<P>
Objective Analysis of EPR Spectra by Computer Methods,
<I>J. Chem Soc., Perkin Trans. 2</I>, 1993, 1991.
<P>
Reaction of [60]Fullerene with Triethylamine.  <I>Fullerene Sc. Tech.</I>, 1995, <STRONG>3</STRONG> ,299. (With N. Pola, A. D. Darwish, H. W. Kroto, M. F. Meidine, A. K. Abdulsada, R. Taylor and D. R. M. Walton.)
<P>
Stabilization of Benzyl Radicals by Substituents.  An EPR Study of <I>Para</I>-Substituted Benzyl Radicals. <I>J. Chem Soc., Perkin Trans. 2</I>, 1996, in the press. (With M. Sharifi.)
<P>
Mechanistic Studies on the Combustion of Isotopically Labelled Cyclohexanes within a Single Cylinder Internal Combustion Engine.  <I> Combust. Sci. Tech.</I>, 1996, in the press. (With D. Gregory and P. J. Bennett.)<P>  
