<HEAD>
<TITLE>Dr. R. Taylor</TITLE>
<meta name="resource-type"
value="document">
<meta name="distribution"
value="global">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<img src="/images/cpes.gif">
<H3>Dr. Roger Taylor</H3>
</CENTER>
<HR>
E-Mail :<A HREF="mailto:r.taylor@sussex.ac.uk"> R. Taylor@Sussex.ac.uk</A>
<P>
There is a need to deposit films of germanium and silicon from volatile precursors at low temperatures
to avoid degradation of the substrate surface. Germanium and Silicon hydrides ( currently used) present 
corrosion and handling problems. Alkyl  derivatives overcome these but thermally are too stable.
We find that towards excimer (UV) photolysis the alkyl derivatives are <ITALIC>less</ITALIC>
stable than the hydrides owing to their grater molecular cross-section. The potential for depositing
films at ambient temperature that this presents is being investigated and developed.
<P>
The closed  - cage  carbon molecules (fullerenes) are at the centre of chemists' attention worldwide
At Sussex the first pure samples of C<SUB>60</SUB> and C<SUB>70</SUB> were isolated, 
and the colours of these materials discovered, and their structures were determined by 
<SUP>13</SUP>C NMR spectroscopy. Current research (in 
collaboration with<A HREF="/faculty/hwk/"> H. W. Kroto</A> 
and<A HREF="/faculty/drmw/"> D. R. M. Walton</A>)
 includes isolation and characterisation  of higher fullerenes, and investigation of the reactions of
 C<SUB>60</SUB> and  C<SUB>70</SUB>, e.g. hydrogenation and
halogenation, photocatalysed oxidation, cycloaddition (2 + 2 and 2+ 4), arylation,  hydroboration and
hydroxylation. The aim is both to determine the reactivity behaviour of the cages and the addition 
patterns associated with them, and to derivatise them, thereby providing pathways for the 
formation of novel compounds. The exceptional acidity of the fullerenes (partially hydrogenated
fullerenes) is being investigated through base-catalysed hydrogen exchange. Studies of hydrogen 
exchange in related aromatic hydrocarbons are also in progress.

<P ALIGN=CENTER> 
<IMG SRC="rt1.gif"><P>
<H3>Selected Publications</H3><P>
Chemical vapour deposition of germanium films by laser-induced photolysis of ethylgermanes
<CITE>J. Chem. Soc. , Faraday Trans.,</CITE> 1992,<STRONG> 88</STRONG>, 1637.<P>
Isolation, separation and characterisation of the fullerenes C<SUB>60</SUB> and C<SUB>70</SUB>: the third form of carbon.
<CITE>J. Chem. Soc. Chem. Commun.,</CITE> 1990, 1423.<P>
Preparation and characterisation of C<SUB>60</SUB>Br<SUB>6</SUB> and C<SUB>60</SUB>Br<SUB>8</SUB>,
<CITE>Nature, </CITE>1992,<STRONG> 357,</STRONG> 479.<P>
Highly oxygenated derivatives of flourinated C<SUB>60</SUB>, and the mode of fragmentation
of the flourinated cage under EI conditions,
<CITE>J. Chem. Soc., Chem. Commun.,</CITE>1993, 875.<P>
<SUP>13</SUP>C NMR spectroscopy of C<SUB>76</SUB>, C<SUB>78</SUB>,C<SUB>84</SUB> 
and mixtures of C<SUB>86</SUB> - C<SUB>102</SUB>. Anomalous chromatographic behaviour of
C<SUB>82</SUB>.
<CITE>J. Chem. Soc., Perkin Trans. 2,</CITE> 1993 1029.
<P>
