<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Professor D.W.Young</TITLE>
<meta name="resource-type"
value="document">
<meta name="distribution"
value="global">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/cpes.gif">
<H3>Professor D. W. Young</H3>
</CENTER>
<HR>
E-Mail <A HREF="mailto:d.w.Young@sussex.ac.uk">D.W.Young@sussex.ac.uk</A><P>
Current research activity centres on understanding the mode of action of drugs and 
the design and synthesis of compounds which should be active as drugs. 
This involves stereospecific synthesis including the design of new synthetic 
methodology and the investigation of the mechanism of action of key target
enzymes
<P>
The group was the first to discover the stereochemistry of the ring closure
step which gives the &beta;-lactam ring in the antibiotic penicillin (<B> 1</B>)
and is currently involved in the synthesis of antibacterial compounds 
acting on the penicillin target enzymes. Crucial discoveries have been made
of differences in the docking of the cancer drug methotrexate ( <B>2</B>) and the 
natural substrate at the active site of a cancer target enzyme dihydrofolate 
reductase. Work on thymidylate synthase has led to a chemical model for this 
important enzyme and current work centres on understanding how the 'suicide 
substrate' 5-flourouracil ( <B>3</B>) inhibits the enzyme in a process important 
to cancer chemotherapy. Stereochemical aspects of enzymes involved in the 
synthesis of antibiotics and in the catabolism of DNA, RNA and the anti-cancer
drug 5-flourouracil ( <B>3</B>) have been discovered. Current work in this area 
centres on the metabolism of D-amino acids that are common in bacteria but 
not in man. Investigation of inhibition of these processes may lead to development of antibacterial drugs.
<P>
Synthetic studies involve asymmetric synthesis of new amino acids and new
methods of synthesis of glutamate agonists and antagonists which are important
as potential central nervous system drugs. Studies on conformational aspects of 
peptide interaction centre on medicinally important peptides and work on 
peptide mimetics should furnish information on drug - receptor interactions.

<P>
<IMG SRC="dwy1.gif"><IMG SRC="dwy2.gif"><IMG SRC="dwy3.gif">
<P>
<STRONG>Selected Publications</STRONG>
<P>
Synthesis of potential agonists and antagonists for central glutamate 
receptors by a novel 'Ring Switching' process.
<CITE>J. Chem. Soc.,Chem Commun.,</CITE>1991, 314
<P>
Synthesis of non-proteinogenic amino-acids with three chiral centres, 
<CITE>Tetrahedron Lett.,</CITE>1991<STRONG>32,</STRONG> 2679
<P>
A versatile synthesis of stereospecifically labelled D-amino acids and
related enzyme inhibitors,<CITE>J. Chem. Soc., Chem. Commun.,</CITE>1991, 1085.
<P>
Stereospecific assignments of the leucine methyl resonances in the 1H
NMR spectrum of <CITE> Lactobacillus casei</CITE> dihydrofolate 
reductase,<CITE>F. E. B. S. Lett.,</CITE> 1993,<STRONG> 318</STRONG>
177.
<P>
Synthesis of naturally occurring 4-alkylideneglutamic acids,<CITE>
Tetrahedron Lett </CITE>, 1993, <STRONG>34,</STRONG> 4667.

