<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Dr. David Walton</TITLE>
<meta name="resource-type"
value="document">
<meta name="distribution"
value="global">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<img src="/images/cpes.gif">
<H3>Dr David R. M. Walton</H3>
</CENTER>
<HR>
Email:<A HREF="mailto:d.r.m.walton@sussex.ac.uk">D. R. M. Walton@Sussex.ac.uk</A><P>
<H4>Carbon Networks</H4><P>
The coupling of silyl-protected alkynes e.g. R3SiC=CH to sp,sp<SUP>2</SUP> and sp<SUP>3</SUP> 
carbon systems provides a versatile route to substrates such as (1) -
(4), which in turn can be used to generate planar or three-dimensional
carbon networks. These networks act as valuable precursors to a wide
range of useful materials including novel hetrocycles, polymers
(including dendrimers) and metal (PI)-complexes. Reactions, especially
those involving cycloadditions to the alkyne moieties, provide a
valuable insight into the electron distribution and polarisability of
extended conjugated systems.
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="drmw1.gif">
<P>
<H3>Fullerene Chemistry</H3>(With <A HREF="/faculty/hwk/">H.W.Kroto</A>, 
<A HREF="/faculty/kp/">K. Prassides</A> &
<A HREF="/faculty/rt/">R. Taylor</A>)<P>
The successful isolation of pure C<SUB>60</SUB> and C<SUB>70</SUB> at Sussex
has led to the evaluation of the chemical reactivity of these closed-cages through a wide
range of reactions including  cycloadditions, halogenation, reduction and allied processes.
Planned research includes extension of this experimental approach to the preparation of
Fullerene - containing polymers and to the development of functional nanotubes 
leading to composite materials. Controlled low - order additions to the Fullerene 
cage remain a major challenge and this topic is being studied for example, through
reactions of recently isolated hydrido fullerenes.
<P>
<H3>Selected Publications</H3>
The reaction of aryl azides and ethyl diazoacetate with bis(trimethylsilyl)polyymes,
Me<SUB>3</SUB>Si(C C)<SUB>n</SUB>SiMe<SUB>3</SUB>(n=2,3),<CITE>J Organometal. Chem.,</CITE>
1988,<STRONG> 341,</STRONG> 247.<P>
The microwave spectrum and semi -  rigid bender analysis of isocyanatoethyne
HC   CNCO,
<CITE>J. Mol. Spectrosc.,</CITE> 1992, <STRONG>152,</STRONG> 152.<P>

The chemistry of fullerenes, <CITE>Nature,</CITE> 1993, <STRONG>363,</STRONG> 685.<P>

Polyynes and the formation of fullerenes, <CITE>Phil. Trans. Roy. Soc. Lond. Ser. A,</CITE>
1993, <STRONG>343,</STRONG> 103.<P>

Formation and stabilisation of the hexa - adduct of cyclopentadiene with C<SUB>60</SUB>
<CITE>J. Chem. Soc. Chem. Commun.</CITE> 1993, 1342.



 
