<HTML>
<TITLE>Professor John M. Murrell</TITLE>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/cpes.gif">
<H1>Professor John N. Murrell</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>
E-Mail:  <A HREF="mailto:j.n.murrell@sussex.ac.uk">J.N.Murrell@sussex.ac.uk</A>
<P>
I am interested in a broad range of problems in theoretical chemistry, 
including the theory of atomic and molecular collisions, valence theory
and inter atomic forces acting in molecules and solids.

The main emphasis in current research is on the structure of solids and
solid surfaces and the relationship between these and the structures of
microclusters.

We have recently derived a new method for determining the potentials in
atomic solids from vibrational (phonon) data and have shown that this
can be applied equally well to metals and non-metals. These potentials
give very satisfactory predictions for the geometries of clusters. For 
example, a carbon potential determined from diamond and graphite gives
a good picture of linear, planar and fullerene carbon clusters. Typical
of our metal results is that for Ca. We reproduce the phonon spectrum of
both known solid phases (fcc and bcc) and get a good picture of the
reaction path between these two.
<P>
<IMG SRC="jnm1.gif" ALT="Spectrum">
<P>
<STRONG>Selected Publications.</STRONG>
<P>
Cluster structures and stabilities from solid state potential,<CITE>J.
Chem Soc., Faraday Trans.</CITE>1992,<STRONG>88,</STRONG>1229.<P>
Potential functions for Cu, Ag, and Au solids and their applications
to clusters of these elements,<CITE>J.Chem Soc., Faraday Trans.</CITE>
1993,<STRONG>89,</STRONG>1659.<P>
The theory of atomic and molecular collisions,<CITE>Chem Soc. Revs.,
</CITE>1992,17.<P>
The hardness factor in rotational inelastic scattering,<CITE>Mol. Phys.</CITE> 
1992,<STRONG>77, </STRONG>727.<P>
Symmetry in superconducting, insulating and metallic phases of doped cuprates, 
<CITE> Physica C</CITE> 1992, <STRONG>196,</STRONG>185
</BODY>
