<HTML>

<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word ">

<META NAME="BUILD" CONTENT="Feb 10 1995">

<TITLE>Professor Anthony J McCaffery	Telephone  01273 606755  Ext 3263
</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="MOLS">

<META NAME="CREATIM" CONTENT="1995:6:8:9:18:">

<META NAME="VERSION" CONTENT="1">

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/cpes.gif">
<H1>Professor Anthony J. McCaffery</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<B> E-mail  <A HREF="mailto:a.j.mccaffery@sussex.ac.uk" >A.J.McCaffery@sussex.ac.uk</A></B>
<P>
Lasers of all forms have had a revolutionary impact on the borderlines
between chemistry and physics.  They bring a new experimental
dimension that allows us to probe the fundamental principles of
science.  Our group uses laser methods, particularly laser spectroscopy
of small molecules, to investigate the physical principles that
govern chemical processes.
<P>
 
<P>
(i)  New spectroscopic methods have been developed for obtaining
the state-to-state differential scattering cross-section in non-reactive
and reactive collisions from high resolution double resonance
spectroscopy.  This method is used to investigate elementary chemical
processes in the gas phase.
<P>
 
<P>
(ii)  Collision-induced processes in molecules may be governed
by the probability of <I>angular momentum</I> transfer, the probability
of energy change being less important.  This fundamentally new
principle is investigated experimentally and theoretically through
quantum state resolved experiments on small molecules.
<P>
 
<P>
(iii)  Dynamical processes at the surface of atomic and molecular
liquids are investigated using molecular beam/laser studies with
small molecules as probes.  Both kinetics and dynamics of molecular
adsorption and desorption at liquid surfaces are revealed by this
novel study.
<P>
 
<P>
(iv)  Guided wave optics in solids has great potential for novel
devices in the rapidly developing field of optoelectronics.  Lasing
action has already been achieved and frequency doubling has been
demonstrated in ion-implanted optical waveguides in this project
with Professor P Townsend from Physics.
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="ajmcc1.gif" ALT="Sorry you cannot display this picture"></CENTER>
<P>Iodine molecules as they interact with the 
surface of polydimethylsilicone liquid in a 
quantum-resolved scattering experiment to 
probe liquid surface energetics
<HR>
