<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Professor Harold Kroto</TITLE>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="MOLS">
<META NAME="CREATIM" CONTENT="1995:6:8:9:19:">
<META NAME="VERSION" CONTENT="1">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/cpes.gif">
<H1>Professor Harold Kroto</H1>
</CENTER><HR>
<IMG  SRC="harryk.gif" ALT="Prof.H.Kroto"></IMG>
<P>
<B> E-mail  <A HREF="mailto:h.w.Kroto@Sussex.ac.uk" >H.W.Kroto@sussex.ac.uk
</A></B>
<P>

The exciting new field of <A HREF="http://www.sussex.ac.uk/Users/kroto/">fullerene science
</A>has its origins in Sussex research on carbon molecules involving 
synthesis, spectroscopy, and radioastronomy.  
The present fullerene programme covers chemistry, physics, materials science, and astrophysics.
<P>
<B>Synthetic chemistry </B>(with R Taylor and D R M Walton) has
been highly successful, producing the first characterised (X-ray,
NMR, IR spectra etc.) multifunctionalised derivatives:
C60H12, C60Cl6, C60Ph6, C60Br6, C60Br8, and complexes C60.(Cp2Fe)2.
<P>
 
<B>Solid state chemistry and physics</B> (with K Prassides): investigations
of electrical, magnetic, and optical behaviour of the new materials
are being carried out.
<P>
 
<B>Exo- and endo-hedral complexes </B>have been generated by new
fullerene formation techniques and monitored by mass spectrometry.
<P>
<B>Nanofibers and nanoparticles</B> are being made and studied
experimentally and theoretically.
<P>
<B>Cluster beam studies</B> (with A J Stace) have shown that small
fullerenes (C24,, C28 etc) are formed during laser vaporisation.
 The dynamics of metal/carbon aggregation is under investigation.
<P>
 <B>Astrophysical studies</B> of carbon in red giant stars which
uncovered the existence of C60 continue; the Kuiper Flying Observatory
is to search for C60 in space, and microparticle investigations
are progressing towards an understanding of dust in space.
<P>

<A HREF="HTTP://tcibm.mols.sussex.ac.uk/kroto/vega.html"><FONT SIZE=4>Vega Trust</FONT></A>
<P>
 <B>Selected Publications</B>
<P>
C60: Buckminsterfullerene, the celestial sphere that fell to earth, <I>Angew. Chem., Int. Edn. Engl.</I>,1992, <B>31,</B> 111.
<P>
The structural characterisation of buckminsterfullerene compounds, <I>J. Mol. Structure</I>, 1993,<B>292</B>, 1.
<P>
 
Formation of carbon nanofibers, <I>J. Phys. Chem.</I>, 1992, <B>96</B>, 6941.
<P>
Fullerene physics, <I>Physics Today</I>, 1992, <B>5</B>, 44.
<P>
A post-buckminsterfullerene view of carbon in the galaxy, <I>Acc. Chem. Res.</I>, 1992, <B>25</B>, 106.
<P>
 
'Molecular rotation spectra', Dover, New York, new edition 1992.
<P>
