<HTML>

<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word ">

<META NAME="BUILD" CONTENT="Feb 10 1995">

<TITLE>Professor Anthony J Stace	Telephone  01273 678619</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="MOLS">

<META NAME="CREATIM" CONTENT="1995:6:8:9:17:">

<META NAME="VERSION" CONTENT="1">

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/cpes.gif">
<H1>Professor Anthony J. Stace</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<B> E-mail  <A HREF="mailto:a.j.stace@sussex.ac.uk" >A.J.Stace@sussex.ac.uk</A></B>
<P>
The study of clusters provides an opportunity to investigate the
ways in which chemical and physical properties of substances develop
as a function of size.  Current programmes involve some of the
fundamental questions concerning materials: for example, how many
metal atoms are required to construct an electrical conductor,
and can a finite collection of atoms or molecules adopt the same
crystalline structure as that observed for the bulk material?
<P>
 
<P>
We have designed and developed a broad range of procedure for
generating and probing the properties of finite collections of
atoms and molecules (clusters) in the gas phase. By use of a variety
of techniques centred on supersonic expansion, clusters of the
form Arn, (H2O)n, (C6H6)n, Aln, Hgn, etc. can be generated for
n in the range 2 - 1000 and detected by advanced mass spectrometric
methods.  Infrared and visible lasers are used to investigate
the physical properties of the clusters, and visible and UV lasers
are used to promote chemical reactions in pure and mixed clusters,
such as (C4H6)n+ and Arn.C4H6+.  Of particular interest in the
latter case are the steric constraints imposed on the fragmentation
pattern of the molecular ion by a &quot;matrix-like&quot; environment.
<P>
 
<P>
New apparatus has been developed for studying the structure and
decay dynamics of cluster and molecular ions.  In these experiments,
neutral photofragments act as &quot;messengers&quot; giving information
about the time scale and energetics of particular decay processes;
a detailed study of the structures of small inert gas cluster
ions, i.e. Ar3+, Kr3+ etc., is in progress. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="ajs1.gif" ALT="Sorry you cannot display images"></CENTER>
<P>
Section of a high resolution mass spectrum recorded for water cluster ions, 
showing the presence of various types of singly, doubly, and triply charged ions
<HR>
<B>Selected Publications</B>
<P>
Structure-reactivity correlations in cluster ions, <I>J. Chem.
Phys., </I>1988, <B>89</B>, 4062.
<P>
Evidence of two stable forms of doubly and triply charged water
cluster, <I>Phys. Rev. Lett., </I>1988, <B>61</B>, 306.
<P>
Observations of Coulomb explosion in doubly charged atomic and
molecular clusters, <I>J. Chem. Phys., </I>1992, <B>96</B>, 408.
<P>
The decay dynamics of photoexcited argon cluster ions, <I>J. Chem.
Phys., </I>1992, <B>97</B>, 1992.
<P>
A molecular dynamics simulation of small benzene clusters, <I>J.
Chem. Phys., </I>1993, <B>98</B>, 3905.
<P>
