<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Dr.N. C. Billingham</TITLE>
<meta name="resource-type"
value="document">
<meta name="distribution"
value="global">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/cpes.gif">
<H3>Dr. Norman C. Billingham</H3>
</CENTER>
<HR>
E-Mail :<A HREF="mailto:n.c.billingham@sussex.ac.uk">N.C.Billingham@Sussex.ac.uk</A>
<P>
There has been a long standing interest in the physical chemistry of degradation and stabilisation
of polymers, in solubility and diffusion of small molecules in polymers and thermosetting resins.
<P>
Most organic polymers emit very low levels of light as a result of their oxidation. We have developed
the application of this<I> chemiluminescence</I> as a method for detecting oxidative degradation
before failure and trying to predict lifetimes of service use. We are currently investigating high - 
sensitivity camera for imaging of oxidative degradation.<P>
We have also developed applications of U. V. and flourescence microscopy to study localised
degradation and the distribution and migration of stabilising additives. Current interests are in
effects of polymer structure on the solubility and diffusion of stabilising additives and in equilibration 
of additives between phases in polymer blends and it's effect on stability. The last problem has many 
implications for the recycling of mixed plastic wastes.

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="./ncb1.gif"><P>
<H3>Collaborative Research</H3><P>
The aim is to develop novel methods for producing polymers with controlled architecture.
<P>
Group - transfer polymerisation is utilised to make narrow distribution homo - and co - polymers and
block copolymers of acrylic and methacrylic  monomers, particularly statistical and block copolymers
containing acid groups. With low concentrations of acid groups the polymers are dispersants for
inorganic particles and are proving very effective in ceramics processing. Higher acid content
gives membranes which combine good mechanical properties with high permeability to ions.
<P>
We are also producing water -  and organic - soluble monodisperse, amphiphilic block copolymers
containing acidic and base groups in the same molecule. Their phase-separation is being studied
in both solid and solution in order to develop applications as dispersants, viscosity modifiers, drug
delivery systems and membranes. Living cationic polymerisation of vinyl ethers is also being used
to prepare water - soluble homo - and block polymers with interesting properties.<P>
We are also (in collaboration with <A HREF="/faculty/fgnc/"> Professor F. G. N. Cloke</A>)
developing new lanthanide catalysts for synthesis of previously inaccessible copolymers of ethane
and acrylic monomers.<P> 

<P ALIGN=CENTER> 
<H3>Selected Publications</H3><P>

Novel colloidal polyaniline-silica composites,<CITE> J. Chem. Soc., Chem. Commun., </CITE>1992, 108<P>
Preparation of novel polypyrrole-silica colloidal nanocomposites, <CITE>J. Colloid Interface Sci.,</CITE> 1993
<STRONG>159,</STRONG> 257.<P>
Chemiluminescence from oxidation of polymers,<CITE> Adv. Stab. and Cont. Deg. Poly.,</CITE> 
1989, <STRONG>2,</STRONG> 11.<P>
U.V. microscopy of polymers - a review,<CITE> Inst. Phys. Conf. Ser.,</CITE> 1989, <STRONG>98,</STRONG> 571<P>
Synthesis of block copolymers with methacrylic acid segments by group-transfer
polyerisation.<CITE> Eur. Polymer J. </CITE>1993,<STRONG> 29</STRONG>, 407.
