<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>How to Get to the Unversity of Sussex at Brighton</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/cpes.gif">   
</CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/Southern.gif">
<P>
<EM>The University of Sussex</EM> is conveniently located on the
outskirts of Brighton, close to the Channel ferry ports and to Gatwick
and Heathrow international airports, and just over an hour by train
from London.
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/Brighton.gif"></A>
<P>
To reach the University if you are travelling by:
<UL>
<LI> <A HREF="#Train">Train...</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#Coach">Coach...</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#Bus">Bus...</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#Car">Car...</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#Taxi">Taxi...</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#Air">Air...</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#Sea">Sea...</A>
</UL>
<HR>
A map of the campus (200kb, JPEG format) is <A /images/Campus.jpg">
available here</A>.
<hr>
<A NAME="Train"><H2>By Train</H2>
</A>
Book through to Falmer Railway Station which is immediately opposite
the University entrance. Some trains on the Coastway line east of
Brighton run direct to Falmer, but travellers from London and on most
other lines will need to change at Brighton or Lewes. Falmer Station
is well served by frequent local trains from Brighton and Lewes (about
eight minutes from either direction) which run until about midnight.
 <P>
<HR>
<A NAME="Coach"><H2>By Coach</H2>
</A>
Coaches to Brighton leave Victoria every 90 minutes from 0900 hours.
The coach arrives in Brighton Pool Valley Bus Station and you should
then take a <A HREF="#Bus">bus</A> to the campus.
 <P>
<hr>
<A NAME="Bus"><H2>By Bus</H2>
</A>
Bus numbers 28, 128 and 729 travel between Brighton (Old Steine) and
Lewes and stop outside the University; bus number 25 runs between
Brighton (Old Steine) and the University and comes to the North end of
Campus.
 <P>
<HR>
<A NAME="Car"><H2>By Car</H2>
</A>
The University is on the main A27 road between Brighton and Lewes,
about four miles (six kilometers) from the centre of Brighton and the
same distance from Lewes. Visitors driving from London should take the
M23/A23, coming off at Patcham to join the A27 eastbound towards
Lewes. Drivers from the West should take the A27 direct to the
University; from the East they should go to Lewes and follow the signs
for Brighton. Visitors may use any of the designated car parks (see <A HREF=  
"/images/Campus.jpg">map</A>) but
should note that the car parks are open and unattended. Cars should be
locked and objects of value should not be left in them.
 <P><HR>
<A NAME="Taxi"><H2>By Taxi</H2>
</A>
Taxis are available at Brighton and Lewes Railway Stations and in
central Brighton, but please note that there is no taxi service at
Falmer Station.
 <P>
<HR>
<A NAME="Air"><H2>By Air</H2>
</A>
If there is a choice of airport, it is advisable to fly to London
(Gatwick) since it is closer to the University than London (Heathrow).
<P>
From Gatwick take the train to Brighton or Lewes and change for
Falmer.
 <P>
From Heathrow take the Underground (London Transport) to Victoria
Railway Station and then take the train to Brighton or Lewes and on to
Falmer; or take the airport bus to Gatwick and go on by train from
there. <P>
<HR>
<A NAME="Sea"><H2>By Sea</H2></A>
From Newhaven, take the train direct to Falmer. From Portsmouth or
Southampton, take the train to Brighton and change there for Falmer.
From all other ports, take the train to London and travel from
Victoria via Brighton or Lewes
<HR>
<A HREF="/index.html"> Back to CPES Home Page</A>
<P>
<HR>
