<html>
<head>
   <title>Kerry Jenkins Homepage</title>
   <meta name="Author" content="Douglas M. Barr">
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/3.0b4Gold (Win16)">
   <meta name="KeyWords" content="DKR, synthesis, CIDR, organic, chemistry, radical, asymmetric, stereochemistry">
</head>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFFC0" link="#0000EE" vlink="#001A8B" alink="#000000" background="kerybck1.gif">

<center><p><font COLOR="#004040"><b><font SIZE=+4>Kerry's Homepage</font></b>.</font></p></center>

<center><p><a href="kerry.gif"><img src="kerrysml.gif" border=2 height=197 width=150></a></p></center>

<ul>
<p><font COLOR="#000040"><font SIZE=+1>After I graduated from Exeter university
in 1992 I spent 12 months at Glaxo Group Research in Greenford (U.K.) before
coming to Sussex to take a Masters degree in Medicinal Chemistry. I now
work for Dr. Steve Caddick and I am in the second year of my D.Phil. which
is essentially exploring methods of stereoselectively manipulating racemic
substrates to give products of enriched stereoisomeric composistion. This
is typically achieved by either transforming the racemate into a prochiral
reactive intermediate which then undergoes a stereoselective reaction or
by a dynamic resolution of the racemate, which requires the stereogenic
centre in the starting material.to be optically labile. A resolution process
(e.g. kinetic or preferential crystallisation) differentiates between the
two stereoisomers and the epimerisation equilibration allows the overall
transformation to proceed to give chirally enriched material in greater
than 50% yield.</font></font></p>

<p><font COLOR="#000040"><font SIZE=+1>References:</font></font></p>

<p><font COLOR="#000040"><font SIZE=+1>Caddick S., Jenkins K.; <i>Tetrahedron
Lett.,</i> <b>37</b>, 1301, 1996. and references therein.</font></font></p>

<p><font COLOR="#000040"><font SIZE=+1>In addition to asymmetric synthesis
I have an interest in free radical chemistry; particulary with respect
to synthetically useful methodology. I have investigated the intramolecular
radical <i>ipso</i> substitution of aromatic sulfones to effect carbon-carbon
bond forming ring closures and the same i<i>pso</i> substitution reaction
has been investigated in an intermolecular sense whereby the aryl sulfone
is displaced by the tri-<i>n</i>-butyl tin radical to give synthetically
useful aryl stannanes under mild, neutral conditions.</font></font></p>

<p><font COLOR="#000040"><font SIZE=+1>References:</font></font></p>

<p><font COLOR="#000040"><font SIZE=+1>Caddick S., Aboutayab K., Jenkins
K., West R.I.,<i> J.Chem.Soc., Perkin Trans. 1</i>, 675, 1996. and references
therein.</font></font></p>

<center><p><img src="m0orf2qb.gif" height=9 width=720></p></center>

<center><p><a href="mailto: k.jenkins@susx.ac.uk"><img src="mailbox2.gif" height=40 width=40 align=abscenter></a><a href="mailto: k.jenkins@susx.ac.uk">&nbsp;E-mail
Kerry</a>.</p></center>
</ul>

<center><p><font COLOR="#004040"><font SIZE=+2><a href="welcome.html">Back
to the Caddick Group&nbsp;Homepage</a></font></font></p></center>

<center><p><i><font COLOR="#004040">Copyright Douglas Barr 14/6/96.</font></i></p></center>

