<DOCNO>WT14-B26-228</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA024-000250-B011-298</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://cpesw3.mols.susx.ac.uk:80/resgrps/sjc/vedhome1.html 139.184.112.250 19970108104558 text/html 2765
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: CERN/3.0
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 11:42:33 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 2557
Last-Modified: Wednesday, 11-Sep-96 11:17:37 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
   <title>Valerie Doyle's Homepage</title>
   <meta name="Author" content="Douglas M. Barr">
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/3.0b4Gold (Win16)">
   <meta name="KeyWords" content="enediyne, neocarzinostatin, A-ring, synthesis, organic, chemistry">
</head>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFFC0" link="#0000FF" vlink="#000000" alink="#0000FF" background="fkrueger.gif">

<center><p><b><font SIZE=+4>Val's Homepage </font></b></p></center>

<center><p><img src="val.jpg" height=229 width=181></p></center>

<p><i><font SIZE=+2>Hi I'm Val, I'm a final year D.Phil. student and I
work for Dr. Steve Caddick at the University of Sussex. My undergraduate
degree was in Chemistry with Business at Kingston, but I decided business
was just too boring to contemplate for life and so here I am working on
the total synthesis of a novel anti-cancer agent, namely the Neocarzinostatin
chromophore.....exciting stuff, huh?.</font></i></p>

<p><i><font SIZE=+2>For those of you thinking she's working on what?, here's
a little background info:</font></i></p>

<p><i><font SIZE=+2>Neocarzinostatin is a member of the class of naturally
ocurring enediyne anti-tumour anti-bacterial agents, which also includes
Calicheamicin and Dynemicin. It occurs naturally as a biologically active
chromophore bound to its apo-protien which provides it with transport and
stability. </font></i></p>

<p><i><font SIZE=+2>Neocarzinostatin's potent anti tumour activity along
with its interesting mode of action has led to much academic interest recently,
but there has yet to be a complete synthesis of the chromophore.</font></i></p>

<p><i><font SIZE=+2>My approach to the synthesis of the A &amp; B rings
of Neocarzinostatin (as outlined below in green, click on the diagram if
you want more detail) is based on a novel Pd mediated cyclisation.</font></i></p>

<center><p><a href="http://www.mols.susx.ac.uk./mols/resgrps/sjc/ncsbig1.gif"><img src="ncssmal2.gif" border=2 height=254 width=300></a></p></center>

<center><p><font SIZE=+3>The Neocarzinostatin Chromophore</font></p></center>

<center><p><img src="blumarbl.gif" border=0 height=8 width=581></p></center>

<center><p><a href="mailto: d.m.barr@sussex.ac.uk"><img src="mailbox2.gif" border=2 height=40 width=40 align=abscenter></a><a href="mailto: d.m.barr@sussex.ac.uk">&nbsp;E-mail
Val</a>.</p></center>

<center><p><font SIZE=+1><a href="/resgrps/sjc/welcome.html">Back
to the Caddick Group Homepage.</a></font></p></center>

</body>
</html>




