<DOCNO>WT14-B26-230</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA024-000250-B011-259</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://cpesw3.mols.susx.ac.uk:80/resgrps/sjc/ssshome1.html 139.184.112.250 19970108104541 text/html 4656
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: CERN/3.0
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 11:42:16 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 4448
Last-Modified: Wednesday, 11-Sep-96 11:19:00 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
   <title>Sakthi Shan Homepage</title>
   <meta name="Author" content="Douglas M. Barr">
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/3.0b4Gold (Win16)">
   <meta name="KeyWords" content="enediyne, neocarzinostatin, A-ring, synthesis, organic, chemistry">
</head>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#000000" link="#FFFFFF00" vlink="#000080" alink="#FFFFFFC0" background="woody.gif">

<center><p><font SIZE=+4>Sakthi's Homepage</font> </p></center>

<center><p><img src="sakthi.jpg" border=0 height=279 width=227></p></center>

<p><font COLOR="#000000"><font SIZE=+1>First here's a little bit about
me........ in case someone out there wants to offer me a job........</font></font></p>

<p><font SIZE=+1>After completing a joint Hons. degree in Chemistry and
Biochemistry at Imperial college, I moved to Steve Caddick's research group.
I am currently in the process of completing my D.Phil. in an organic synthesis
project.</font></p>

<p><font SIZE=+1>I am also a very keen football fan and support one of
the best teams in England .... Nott's Forest...</font></p>

<center><p><a href="http://www.noord.bart.nl/%7Earjenjkl/forest.html"><img src="notts1.gif" border=2 height=160 width=94></a></p></center>

<center><p><i>Click on the Best Logo in the Land to visit their Homepage!</i></p></center>

<center><p><i><font SIZE=+2>And now for the chemistry......</font></i></p></center>

<center><p><b><i><font SIZE=+3>Model Studies Directed Towards the Asymmetric
Synthesis of the Neocarzinostatin Chromophore. </font></i></b></p></center>

<p><font SIZE=+1><b><i>Introduction</i></b> Neocarzinostatin Chromophore
A (<b><i><a href="ncsbig1.gif">NCS Chrom A, 59k .gif image</a></i></b>)is
part of a family of naturally occurring enediyne anti-cancer antibiotics.
They have received much attention due to their potent biological activities
and novel modes of action. We were intrigued by the structural complexity
of NCS Chrom A, which to date has eluded total synthesis. Our work has
been focused on developing an asymmetric route to the A ring of NCS chrom
A, utilising a novel silyl cuprate based methodology. We will show how
a successful model study led us to tackle the real system. Discussion The
retrosynthetic analysis that we envisaged for NCS chrom A (below) shows
that the A ring portion 1 was a key intermediate. </font></p>

<center><p><img src="web1.gif" border=0 height=267 width=900></p></center>

<p><font SIZE=+1><b><i>Model Study</i>.</b> We decided to make a model
A ring precursor containing one hydroxy functionality. The known compound
2 was readily converted to the acetylenic aldehyde. </font></p>

<center><p><img src="web2.gif" border=0 height=142 width=871></p></center>

<p><font SIZE=+1>The aldehyde was subsequently treated with TMS cuprate
to yield the cyclised product 3 in 35%. The real system. Encouraged by
this result we proceeded with the real system. The strategy employed was
the use of the Sharpless Asymmetric dihydroxylation reaction (A.D.) as
the means of introduction of the two hydroxy groups, with the correct relative
and absolute stereochemistry. To this end, the enynol 4 and its TMS deprotected
counterpart were protected with various groups and treated both forms of
the A.D. Mix. Our results indicated that the PMP protecting group gave
the best result with diol 5 being prepared in 90% yield. </font></p>

<center><p><img src="web3.gif" border=0 height=146 width=928></p></center>

<p><font SIZE=+1>After suitable protection, deprotection and oxidation,
the diol aldehyde was treated with our cuprate reagent and initial results
indicate the presence of cyclised product 6. In conclusion, we have developed
an asymmetric route to the A ring of our target molecule, which is suitably
substituted to allow further elaboration. </font></p>

<p><b>Reference. . K.C. Nicolaou et.al. Angew Chemie., 1991, 30, 1987.
</b></p>

<center><p><font SIZE=+2><a href="/resgrps/sjc/welcome.html">Back to the Caddick Group Homepage.</a></font></p></center>
<center><p><img src="mdlline.gif" height=9 width=588></p></center>

<center><p><a href="mailto: s.shanmugathasan@sussex.ac.uk"><img src="mailbox2.gif" border=2 height=40 width=40 align=abscenter></a><a href="mailto: s.shanmugathasan@sussex.ac.uk">&nbsp;E-mail
Sakthi</a>.</p></center>
<center><p><i>Copyright Douglas Barr, 14/6/96.</i></p></center>

</body>
