<A NAME="New in V2.5"></A><H2>New in TCompress V2.5</H2>
<P>Here's what we've added:
<UL>
<LI><B>TargetPath, MakeDirectories</B> and <B>ExceptionOnFileError</B> properties to make expanding files from multi-file archives a one-liner
<LI><B>Key</B> property for protecting compressed data
<LI><B>LoadCompressedResource</B> and <B>LoadExpandedResource</B> functions for extracting compressed resources from your EXE or DLL -- ideal for making self-extracting EXEs
<LI>Fewer dependencies in the Compress unit means much smaller  "no-forms" applications are now possible
<LI>Example applets for self-extracting EXEs and loading compressed bitmaps from your EXE
<LI>Several other minor changes and additions to make your data compression jobs easier
</UL>
<P>As always, we've kept a very high level of backwards compatibility with previous versions. Best of all, <I>for registered TCompress V2.0 users, the upgrade is free of charge.</I>
<P><A HREF="http://www.spis.co.nz/compress.zip>Download V2.5 today! (180K)</A>

<H4>Upgrade prices for TCompress V1.5 Registered Users:</H4>
<P>Registration upgrade: $ NZ 35 (approx $US 25)<BR>
If you bought the V1.5 Compress unit source, the upgrade fee above includes a source upgrade.</P>
<P>For proof of registration, please supply your V1.5 <U>RegName</U> and <U>RegNumber</U>. For proof of source code ownership, please supply the first four comment lines of the Compress unit source.</P>

<P>To order your upgrade, contact <A HREF="#Contact>SPIS</A> directly.

<P>Come back soon to find about about new TCompress developments and add-ons.
<HR>
<A NAME="TSegCompress"></A><H2><A HREF="http://www.mindspring.com/~kmcclain/index.htm">
TSegCompress 2.51</A></H2>

<P><A HREF="mailto:kmcclain@mindspring.com">Ken McClain</A> has released a new version of his <A HREF="http://www.mindspring.com/~kmcclain/index.htm">
TSegCompress</A> "wrapper" component for TCompress v2.5. This component lets you split archives into multiple chunks. For example, use <A HREF="http://www.mindspring.com/~kmcclain/index.htm">
TSegCompress</A> to break an archive into 1.44MB chunks for backing up to floppy disk, and then to splice them all back together.

<P>The new version has some improvements and includes support for Delphi 1.0 and 2.0. Credit card registrations for TSegCompress are now possible by registering through us, or you can register via check with Ken if you prefer.

<P>Go <A HREF="http://www.mindspring.com/~kmcclain/index.htm">
get it!</A>
<HR>
<A NAME="Tips & Tricks"></A><H2>Tips & Tricks</H2>
<P>
"I found that best compression rates on large tables are achieved by using first coRLE to squeeze the table quickly into 25% of it's original size and then coLZH to finish it up. It gives the best compression/time ratio and the best compression rate ever: 1,076,152 bytes squeezed down to 39,300bytes." <BR>
<I>Bob Heida (bobtsf@login.cz)</I></P>

<P>"I tweaked the Compress method source so it <I>always</I> puts a header in compressed blobs. Having done that, I can now compress multiple items into a single database field -- very useful if you have a range of information to store in a single record."<BR>
<I>Lee Slater (lees@motelnet.co.nz)</I></P>

<P>If you have any tips of your own to add, or particular usage  questions, please email <A HREF="mailto:peter@spis.co.nz>Peter Hyde.</A>

<HR>     
<P><A NAME="Reviews"></A><H2>News and Reviews: What TCompress users have said, and what they're doing with it</H2></P>
<P>
"First let me thank you for one of the most well crafted shareware Delphi components I have seen. I greatly appreciate those who have gone the extra step to turn a "program" into a "product....."<BR>
<I>Integral Scientific Software, Fort Collins, CO 80525-1799, USA.</I></P>

<P>"I was, and am still, impressed with the level of service you provided. You went out of your way, even before we bought the product, to work with me (by sending code, examples, etc)... and I really appreciate
it!  Your level of service is extraordinary. I wish that all of the people we dealt with were as accomodating as you."<BR>
<I>Tom Bowden (tom@Rheyn.COM)</I></P>

<P>"It took me less than a day to implement your tcompress in a dll that's backwards API compatible with our old library. It is a god-given control ! (my P120-NT-box made an overnight compression burn-in test. I stopped it this morning with 15731 successfull compression iterations).... (far better than my good old compress.dll and PK libraries)."<BR>
<I>Bob Heida (bobtsf@login.cz)</I></P>

<P>"Thanks for sending TCompress to me. I'm very impressed with it. It is the first component I've found that does what I want it to... and more.I didn't realize you could compress image and memo fields -- that's also a huge advantage for the program I'm working on."<BR>
<I> Mike Yui, Queens University (3mry@qlink.queensu.ca)</I></P>

<P>"We just got a shareware version of TCompress from The Delphi Station - and we love it very much."<BR>
<I>(matej.jaksa@ijs.si  and kres@eunet.si)</I></P>

<P>"Classy stuff!  Well-designed, intuitive.  I was able to use it without a glance at any help or instructions."
<BR> <I>Lou Garner (lou.garner@lunatic.com)</I></P>

<P>"Thank you for an exceptional component."
<BR><I>Graham Colwell (teracomc@mlmpro.com)</I></P>

<P>"I'm using your TCompress in an application I'm developing that communicates with international language translation services.  And BTW, thanks for a GREAT component!  It
seems to find its way into almost everything I do, (hence the need to purchase another license for my day job)."
<BR> <I>David M Trump (dtrump@hach.com)</I></P>

<P>"I was silly enough to try and rescue my schedule by picking up your
compression component last week, and guess what... IT
WORKED WONDERFULLY!<BR>
<P>"Thank you, I absolutely love your component, it saved me a ton of time and
helped me get that app out on time."<BR>
<I>Phillip D. Clark" (phildc@beetu.com)</I>

<P>"Well, I just tested using TCompress with images in Interbase and it works just fine. The trick seems to be to set the TCblobfield size to 1. It's the same you'd write for any other SQL database I think." <BR>
<I>Ricky Engberg (ricky.engberg@microlan.se)</I>

<P>"I appreciate your support... the product [I had to get ready for Comdex] is <A HREF="http://www.mediaminds.com"><I>PictureAlbum for Windows</I></A> (made for Mediaminds Inc)...
<P>"...Tcompress continues to perform well for me. I have included it in <A HREF="http://web2.airmail.net/nunnally">Projector for Windows v4.1,</A> -- a windows screen saver that uses a powerful image engine for the front end and a database for the backend.  Each database is actually 3 files, the database file, a memo file which contains the image blobs, and an index.
<P>"I use Tcompress to archive these files together, so that the user need not be bothered with tracking several files. The database file, which is basically an index, is highly compressible with LZH. One of the things I point out to customers is that my archive files can actually GROW if you try to 'zip' them."
<BR> <I>Bruce Nunnally (nunnally@iadfw.net )</I></P>
<HR>
<A NAME="Products"></A><H2>Other SPIS Products</H2>
<P><A HREF="http://www.spis.co.nz/webcentr/webview.htm">SPIS Webview,</A> a compact offline Web browser with several unique features for creating and distributing demonstration sites and applications on CDROM or floppy disk.
<P><A HREF="http://www.spis.co.nz/webcentr/webwatch.htm">SPIS WebWatch,</A> a Web site monitor which can check any number of sites or pages and automatically report problems and even attempt to fix them!

<H2>And We Highly Recommend:</H2>

<P><A HREF="http://www.gfi-mbh.com/index.htm">DBExtender 2.1.</A> Forget Infopower or Orpheus -- this high-function navigator bar replacement gives you easy access to incremental searches, filtering, find/find-next and table view/edit for <I>any</I> table in your project -- all with one remarkably easy-to-use component.
<P><A HREF="webcentr/webhub.htm">Webhub Site Automation Components.</A> If you're making interactive or database-driven sites, look no further. Webhub has unmatched power, performance and scalability in the site development world.  As used in our <A HREF="http://www.NetTravel.co.nz">NetTravel NZ</A> site.
<P><A HREF="www.o2a.com">TUTIL</A> -- Alec Bergamini's excellent Table Repair Utility interface component for Delphi 1.0 and 2.0.

