<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE> Society For Creative Anachronism</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#770000" >

<table>
<TR>
  <TD><IMG SRC="images/scadragl.gif" alt=""></TD>
  <TD><H1>Welcome to the Current Middle Ages!</H1>
           <H2>The Society For Creative Anachronism</H2></td>
  <TD><IMG SRC="images/scadragr.gif" alt=""></TD>
</TR>
</table>

<P>There was a time when honour was all, a time of courtly love, tournaments fought for a lady's honour, a time when people were respected for the nobility of their characters and the skills of their hands, voices and minds. Once there was a dream of the power of individuals to live by a code of truth and honour.

<P>The dream still lives.

<P>The Society for Creative Anachronism strives to brings the dreams and ideals of the Middle Ages into the present day by actively recreating those aspects of medi&aelig;val life most favourable to the continuation of the dream (but with the benefits of indoor plumbing...).

<P>Now reaching its 30th year, and with 50,000 or so members <A HREF="http://www.ecst.csuchico.edu/~rodmur/sca/
">worldwide</A>, the SCA provides a a welcoming environment where you can make these Current Middle Ages yours to enjoy, whether you're into feasting or fighting in tournaments, costuming or calligraphy, dancing or dalliance. A vast compendium of information about the SCA's Knowne Worlde can be found in the <A HREF="http://www.pbm.com/~lindahl/rialto/rialto.html
">Rialto Archive.</A>

<P>While authenticity is encouraged, the SCA is also about fun and fellowship. We may sing 16th-century madrigals, but you might also find us singing the following:

<P align=center>Those men aren't wearing dresses, sir<BR>
Those are not pantyhose<BR>
No, those are tights and tunics, sir<BR>
They're medi&aelig;val clothes<BR>
And men were really macho then<BR>
As everybody knows<BR>
So kindly do not look at us that way, that way<BR>
For we are your local SCA.

<P align=center>(to the tune of <CITE>God Rest Ye Merry, Gentlemen</CITE>)

<P>New Zealand's first SCA branch, the <A href="http://www.spis.co.nz/spis/phil/southron.htm">Barony of Southron Gaard</A>, is some dozen years old, and there are now groups springing up around the country, ensuring that there will be a feast or fighters' practice, archery shoot or armoury workshop, embroidery meeting or entertaining revel someplace near just about anywhere. Southron Gaard is part of the Kingdom of <A HREF="http://emporium.turnpike.net/Z/zen/SCA/caid.html">Caid</A>.

<P><IMG SRC="images/nz.gif" ALT="NZ Group Locations">

<H2>Regnum</H2>

<P><STRONG>Barony of Southron Gaard</STRONG> (Christchurch)<BR>
<EM>Baron and Baroness</EM>:Their Excellencies Sigurd Hardtrader and Eleonora van den Bogaerde (Nick Turner and Simone Hindin)<BR>
<IMG SRC="images/letters.gif"> Email: <A HREF="mailto:nick@hindin.co.nz">mailto:nick@hindin.co.nz</A> or <A HREF="mailto:simone@hindin.co.nz">mailto:simone@hindin.co.nz</A>

<P><EM>Seneschal</EM>: Master Matsuyama Yoshitoshi (Dorian Davis)<BR>
Tel: (03) 352-4434<BR>
<IMG SRC="images/letters.gif"> Email: <A HREF="mailto:tanuki@takamori.southern.co.nz">mailto:tanuki@takamori.southern.co.nz</A></P>

<P><STRONG><A href="http://www.geocities.com/Vienna/1462">College of Reannag Fhara</A></STRONG> (University of Canterbury, Christchurch)<BR>
<EM>Seneschal</EM>: Lord Gilbert de Montfort (Richard Sutton)<BR>
<IMG SRC="images/letters.gif"> Email: <A HREF="mailto:e.bond@zool.canterbury.ac.nz">e.bond@zool.canterbury.ac.nz</A>

