<HEAD>
<TITLE>New Zealand Science Monthly</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000099" BGCOLOR="#ffffcc">

<table>
<tr>
   <td><H1><CITE><IMG SRC="../images/nzsmlogo.gif" height=66 width=240 ALIGN=top alt="New Zealand Science Monthly"></CITE></H1></td>
   <td width="16%"><A HREF="../changes.htm">Last updated</A><BR>
      <!--Webber_Auto_StampDNR--><!--DS-->16 Aug 96<!----></td>
   </tr>
</table>

<TABLE>
<TR>
   <TD valign=top><H1>Welcome to the <CITE>New Zealand Science Monthly</CITE></H1>
      <P>If you want to know what's going on in New Zealand science, have <I>we</I> got a magazine for <I>you!</I>

<P>Every issue is stuffed to the gills with the latest in ground-breaking research and technology done right here in New Zealand. We frequently carry information about new research and discoveries <I>two or three years</I> ahead of the mainstream media.

<H3>Great stories!</H3>

<P>We don't pull punches. <A HREF="../people.htm#Vicki">Vicki Hyde's</A> editorials are so pithy, popular and universally relevant that she virtually has a space reserved for her on National Radio's <CITE>Sunday Supplement.</CITE>

<P>Vicki's not alone, either. Our <STRONG>Retorts</STRONG> and <STRONG>Viewpoint</STRONG> pages are alive with debates about everything from possum poisoning to the purpose of science, written by people who <STRONG>care.</STRONG><BR>

<P>Then there's the:</P>
<UL>
<LI>news briefs (<STRONG>Quick Dips</STRONG> and <STRONG>Over the Horizon</STRONG>) that keep you up-to-date with what's happening around the country and overseas</LI>

<LI>features which cover a vast range of topics, from the technology of helping the blind see to the fiery debate on fluoridation, from how extraterrestrial material may have kick-started life on this planet to finding out about pioneering science
in New Zealand's pioneering days</LI>

<LI><STRONG>Spotlight</STRONG> profiles, which show that there's usually a heart and humour to be found under the white coat of the stereotypical scientist</LI>

<LI>science education issues covered in <STRONG>Discovery</STRONG>, from science fair ideas to teacher resource material, student science tours and curriculum extensions</LI>

<LI>puzzles in <STRONG>Neurobics</STRONG> designed to exercise the brain, and the occasional dark humour of the <STRONG>Black Hole</STRONG>

<LI>last (but not least) where else can you get a regular fix of <A HREF="../people.htm#Nick">Nick Kim's</A> weird and wonderful cartoons?</LI>
</UL>

<H3>Free sample</H3>

<P>Don't take our word for it -- <A href="subscrib.htm">contact us</A> today for a free sample copy.
</TD>
   <TD valign=top><h3>On-Line Contents</h3>
