<A NAME="New in V2.5"></A><H2>New in TCompress V2.5</H2>
<P>Here's what we've added:
<UL>
<LI><B>TargetPath, MakeDirectories</B> and <B>ExceptionOnFileError</B> properties to make expanding files from multi-file archives a one-liner
<LI><B>Key</B> property for protecting compressed data
<LI><B>LoadCompressedResource</B> and <B>LoadExpandedResource</B> functions for extracting compressed resources from your EXE or DLL -- ideal for making self-extracting EXEs
<LI>Fewer dependencies in the Compress unit means much smaller  "no-forms" applications are now possible
<LI>Example applets for self-extracting EXEs and loading compressed bitmaps from your EXE
<LI>Several other minor changes and additions to make your data compression jobs easier
</UL>
<P>As always, we've kept a very high level of backwards compatibility with previous versions. Best of all, <I>for registered TCompress V2.0 users, the upgrade is free of charge.</I>
<P><A HREF="http://www.spis.co.nz/compress.zip>Download V2.5 today! (180K)</A>

<H4>Upgrade prices for TCompress V1.5 Registered Users:</H4>
<P>Registration upgrade: $ NZ 35 (approx $US 25)<BR>
If you bought the V1.5 Compress unit source, the upgrade fee above includes a source upgrade.</P>
<P>For proof of registration, please supply your V1.5 <U>RegName</U> and <U>RegNumber</U>. For proof of source code ownership, please supply the first four comment lines of the Compress unit source.</P>

<P>To order your upgrade, contact <A HREF="#Contact>SPIS</A> directly.

<P>Come back soon to find about about new TCompress developments and add-ons.
<HR>
<A NAME="TSegCompress"></A><H2><A HREF="http://www.mindspring.com/~kmcclain/index.htm">
TSegCompress 2.51</A></H2>

<P><A HREF="mailto:kmcclain@mindspring.com">Ken McClain</A> has released a new version of his <A HREF="http://www.mindspring.com/~kmcclain/index.htm">
TSegCompress</A> "wrapper" component for TCompress v2.5. This component lets you split archives into multiple chunks. For example, use <A HREF="http://www.mindspring.com/~kmcclain/index.htm">
TSegCompress</A> to break an archive into 1.44MB chunks for backing up to floppy disk, and then to splice them all back together.

<P>The new version has some improvements and includes support for Delphi 1.0 and 2.0. Credit card registrations for TSegCompress are now possible by registering through us, or you can register via check with Ken if you prefer.

<P>Go <A HREF="http://www.mindspring.com/~kmcclain/index.htm">
get it!</A>
<HR>
<A NAME="Tips & Tricks"></A><H2>Tips & Tricks</H2>
<P>
"I found that best compression rates on large tables are achieved by using first coRLE to squeeze the table quickly into 25% of it's original size and then coLZH to finish it up. It gives the best compression/time ratio and the best compression rate ever: 1,076,152 bytes squeezed down to 39,300bytes." <BR>
<I>Bob Heida (bobtsf@login.cz)</I></P>

<P>"I tweaked the Compress method source so it <I>always</I> puts a header in compressed blobs. Having done that, I can now compress multiple items into a single database field -- very useful if you have a range of information to store in a single record."<BR>
<I>Lee Slater (lees@motelnet.co.nz)</I></P>

<P>If you have any tips of your own to add, or particular usage  questions, please email <A HREF="mailto:peter@spis.co.nz>Peter Hyde.</A>

<HR>     
