<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Webhub Site Automation Framework<BR>
<SMALL>Authorised Technical Support Centre</SMALL>
</H1>

<TABLE ALIGN=CENTER><TR><TD>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#Stop">Stop Press! February Seminar</A>
<LI><A HREF="#What">What is Webhub?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#Why">Why Automated Sites?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#Our">Our Webhub-related Services</A>
<LI><A HREF="#Webhub">Webhub Resource List</A>
</UL>
</TD><TD><A HREF="http://www.href.com"><IMG SRC="images/webhub.gif" WIDTH="172" HEIGHT="100" Alt="HREF/Webhub Logo"></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<A NAME="Stop"></A><H2>Stop Press Stop Press Stop Press -- February Seminar</H2>
<P>Ann Lynnworth and Michael Ax, the principals of HREF Tools Corp, USA, will be giving a <B>two day Webhub training seminar in Auckland on February 17th and 18th, 1997.</B>
<P>This will be an intensive two-day course on building WebHub applications, presented by Ann. Day One will provide a solid review of the WebHub framework: CGI architecture, HTML, Web Action Components and Database Components. Day Two will get into building custom web action components with an emphasis on electronic commerce.
<P>The course is lecture-style using a data projector. Do bring a laptop if you have one; printed lecture notes/workbook will be provided. On the evening of day one we will have an informal "code clinic" when you can work on your own projects or the examples from class. Michael Ax will be available to answer questions during the code clinic.
<P>Course cost will be $NZ870+GST for the two days, with 10% discount for registrations received by Feb 1st, and a further 10% for registered Webhub users. Discounts are also available for multiple attendees from the same organisation.
<P>For further information and a secure registration form, see <A HREF="http://www.tradesrv.com.au/href/">Seminar Details.</A>

<P>NB: Ann and Michael will also be speaking at:
<UL>
<LI>Delphi User Group meeting on Wednesday February 12th in Auckland (tentatively from 4pm) at the Westhaven Marina Rowing Club
<LI>Delphi User Group meeting on Thursday February 13th in Christchurch from 6:30pm at ADDLink College, 271 Madras St
</UL>
<P>They are knowledgeable and entertaining speakers, so you shouldn't miss a chance to see them in action...
<P>Email <A HREF="mailto:peter@spis.co.nz">Peter Hyde</A> for further information.


<A NAME="What"></A><H2>What is Webhub?</H2>

<P>Webhub is a state-of-the-art <A HREF="#Why">Web site automation</A> product from <A HREF="http://www.href.com">HREF Tools Corporation.</A> Compared to other <A HREF="automate.htm">automation</A> products for Windows 95 and NT, Webhub has some very significant advantages:

<UL>
<LI><B>Server independence.</B> As the Web server market grows and evolves, Webhub permits migration from one server to another with zero code changes.
<LI><B>Session management.</B> Webhub automatically "saves state", ensuring that each surfer has their own, independent "session" when visiting your site. Many competing automation approaches completely fail to take account of this, resulting in situations where Surfer B can end up staring at Surfer A's data!
<LI><B>Separation of HTML from programming.</B> Webhub's structure means page layout can remain the province of Web designers, while programmers can concentrate on functionality, security, business rules and database connections.
<LI><B>Surfer tracking.</B> Webhub's HUBLOG feature allows each surfer's visit to be fully recorded for later analysis.
<LI><B>Easy site maintenance.</B> Strong support for reusable macros and HTML "chunks" means that URLs, headers, footers etc. which are used all over the site can be changed in just one location.
<LI><B>Performance.</B> Apart from its <A HREF="http://www.href.com:8010/scripts/runisa.dll?HTSM:whyfast">in-built performance features,</A> Webhub allows you to develop fast, scalable Web applications using <A HREF="http://www.borland.com">Borland Delphi,</A> a robust, object-oriented and full-featured compiler language.
<LI><B>Scalability.</B> As site traffic grows, Webhub can scale performance by running additional copies of your Web applications, additional Web servers and even cross-server application execution using it's "Maitre-D'Hub".
<LI><B>Database connectivity.</B> Using the Borland Database Engine, ODBC or Borland's Client/Server links, Webhub applications can bring any of today's most popular database formats to the Web.
<LI><B>High-level functionality.</B> Out of the box, Webhub has support,  customisable components or working demonstration code for:
<UL>
<LI>Form-mail processing (sending form data as email)
<LI>Database table display
<LI>File uploads
<LI>Remote administration
<LI>Scrollable/pageable table grids
<LI>User authentication
<LI>And quite a lot more! (see <A HREF="http://www.href.com:8010/scripts/runisa.dll?HREFSITE:sample">Webhub Demos)</A>
</UL>
</UL>
<P>Webhub is most suitable for applications which go <I>beyond</I> displaying some static pages and a few fields from a database. Tools which come with most of today's servers will usually go that far. Webhub excels where features like electronic commerce, custom searching, security, browser independence, sessions, dynamic pages, data entry and two-way communication (e.g. faxmail) are required. And it is ideal for getting the most value and performance from an Intranet.

<P>A wide range of <A HREF="http://www.href.com:8010/scripts/runisa.dll?HTSM:homepage">public Web sites</A> worldwide have been built with Webhub, including our own <A HREF="http://www.NetTravel.co.nz">NetTravel New Zealand</A> accommodation search engine.

<P>Why not <A HREF="http://www.href.com:8010/scripts/runisa.dll?HREFSITE:trywhub">download a trial version</A> now?

<A NAME="Why"></A><H2>Why Automated Sites?</H2>

<P>High-impact Web sites fall into two categories:
<UL><LI>Those which look beautiful (though often at the expense of download time or browser independence)
<LI>Those that <B>WORK,</B> providing a service or function which brings surfers back to them time and again. Covering everything from book catalogues and weather predictions to shopping malls, interactive puzzles and search engines, working Web sites are now making the running on the Web.
</UL>
<P>As time goes on, more and more effort is going into preparing material for web pages. Excellent new tools such as Microsoft Frontpage or Borland Intrabuilder have been developed to help this process along.

<P>However, when your business information is already present in existing databases or documents, the ideal solution is to present this information with appropriate security and filtering while eliminating manual intervention or conversion steps. This process is another form of site automation.

<A NAME="Our"></A><H2>Our Webhub-related Services</H2>
<P>There are several ways we can help you get up to speed with Webhub:
<UL>
<LI>Webhub introduction and training -- helping you or your
development staff to get up to speed with Webhub, it's key features
and benefits for an automated Internet or Intranet Web site

<LI>Webhub technical consultancy -- leveraging your development
efforts with on-site, telephone and email support

<LI>Site co-development -- you concentrate on the look-and-feel of
your site and we'll produce the Webhub applications to make it hum

<LI>Full site design and development, from needs analysis, initial
specification, structural outline, graphical and user interface
design through to software implementation, hosting, site status and
reliability monitoring

<LI>Advice on site design and hosting issues, especially for
automated Web sites

<LI>Complementary products such as our <A HREF="webview.htm">SPIS Webview</A> offline browser,
and <A HREF="webwatch.htm">Webwatch site monitor</A> and <A HREF="../compress.htm">TCompress File and Database Compression</A> components.
</UL>
<P>Some successful Webhub sites we've developed or consulted on
include:

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.NetTravel.co.nz">NetTravel New Zealand</A> -- a set of six
highly automated sites including custom search engine, faxmail,
database-driven pages, remote administration, security and accounting
functions. Contact: <A HREF="mailto:admin@NetTravel.co.nz">Graham Crocombe</A> (admin@Nettravel.co.nz)

<LI><A HREF="http://www.chchpoly.ac.nz">Christchurch Polytechnic</A> -- a largely static site whose 1200 pages of
course and paper related information are quickly generated from a database
using Webhub. Contact: <A HREF="mailto:fieldg@lib.chchp.ac.nz">Guy Field</A> (fieldg@lib.chchp.ac.nz)

<LI>Southpower Ltd's Intranet site, which went from "what is possible?"
to a fully operational prototype of several key functions in under a
month. Contact: <A HREF="mailto:harrism@southpower.co.nz">Mark Harris</A> (harrism@southpower.co.nz)
</UL>

<P>If we can help you with your Webhub or site automation planning and implementation, <A HREF="mailto:peter@spis.co.nz">just ask!</A>
