<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Why NTs Arel Becoming More Common as Web Servers</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#ccffff">
<TABLE width="100%">
<TR>
<TD><H1><IMG SRC="images/webcentr.gif" width=400 height=222 Alt="WebCentre"></H1>
<TD><H3>Site Design and Automation Specialists</H3></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Discussion Document<BR>
<SMALL>&quot;Why More and More Internet Service Providers are offering Windows- and Mac-based platforms.&quot;</SMALL>
</H1>
<P><I>This document was originally written in December 1995, predicting rapid growth the the number of Windows hosted Web sites. As of October 1996, its predictions seem to have been borne out...</I>
<P><OL>
<LI>The Web market is exploding (stats available, but we all know them anyway)</LI>
<LI>Consequently every Joan and her dog are starting to consider putting their product/organisation/membership/recipe/catalogue/you-name-it information on-line, for better or worse.</LI>
<LI>Larger companies who use Unix/VMS/etc based machines generally get their own Net connection rather than using independent service providers (ISPs) for site hosting. The small to medium and personal computer world is therefore where the ISPs will reap their market.
<LI>In that market segment, 80-90% of the &quot;sharp end&quot; (i.e. sales oriented) information is held on PCs, maybe more. [This is picked entirely out of the air, but I bet it would stand up if tested]</LI>
</OL>
<P>Thus, the <EM>source</EM> of existing information which is likely to be placed on-line is any number of PC or Mac based databases, word processor documents and occasionally spreadsheets.
</P>
<P>A Web site developer is thus left with a few alternative ways of getting it on-line:
<OL TYPE="a">
<LI>Create static HTML pages <EM>once</EM>, and update by hand as required (we've done this)
<LI>Create static HTML pages on a regular basis, updating in toto using a conversion utility (we've done this too)
<LI>Create a form of searchable/interactive flat-file database on Unix by converting the PC data (no fun at <I>all</I> the first time)
<LI>Implement a Web front-end to an existing PC database via Win-CGI or ISAPI on a Windows-based server (our experiences of doing this using <A HREF="webhub.htm">Webhub</A> have been relatively pain-free)
</OL>
<P>Note that, in contrast to (a) to (c), option (d) requires no conversion step. It also means that the developer gets to use their programming language and operating system of choice -- which is bound to lead to higher productivity. It also means they can fully install, debug and test-bed the system in-house, not over a Unix $$/hour shell link to their service provider. These are very significant benefits which no developer will ignore.
</P>
<P>Of course, if it were only a matter of cozening a couple of diehard Unix-phobe developers, it would be of no concern. But quite apart from those developers who are more comfortable in the Windows world, there is the massive market of PC users (all obtaining HTML and CGI add-ons and export functions for their current apps) who represent the main growth area in Web users. At this moment, they don't know they want a service provider who has a Windows host option. But in a matter of months, they'll be demanding it -- warts and all.
</P>
<P>And there are warts, naturally enough -- performance on an NT server is arguably lower than an equivalent Unix or Linux machine, and security may take more effort to get a workable solution. But performance isn't everything -- otherwise we'd all be closing Netscape whenever the transfer rate drops below our modem speed.
</P>
<P>Nevertheless, the ISP who gets an NT box and sticks it alongside their Sun whizz-bangs will probably fare better in the marketplace than those who don't.
</P>
<H2>IMHO. &lt;g&gt;
</H2>

<P><A HREF="mailto:peter@spis.co.nz">Peter Hyde,</A><BR>
Development Director<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.spis.co.nz">South Pacific Information Services Ltd</A><BR>
Author of <A HREF="http://www.spis.co.nz/climb.htm"><CITE>Climbing Out on the Web -- a Web Site Primer</CITE></A>
</P>
<P>
