<HEAD>
<TITLE>NZSM April 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY TEXT="#000099" BGCOLOR="#ffffcc">
<A name="top"></A>
<H1><CITE><IMG SRC="../images/nzsmlogo.gif" height=66 width=240 ALIGN=top alt="New Zealand Science Monthly"></CITE> In the April issue:</H1>

<H2> Quick Dips</H2>

<UL>
<LI>Ever wanted to see a sheep - without the blood and guts? Dissection has been made easier with Aries, the Digital Sheep, put together by AgResearch and a team of Taieri High School students. 
</LI>

<LI>Frogs are disappearing all over the world and New Zealand scientists are part of an international effort to find out what's happening to the amphibians in a new monitoring programme.
</LI>

<LI>IRL researchers have found a way to calibrate highly accurate temperature-measuring equipment  for one-hundredth the cost of conventional approaches.

</UL>

<H2>When will the Mosquitoes Strike?</H2>

<P>Diseases carried by mosquitoes are on the increase all over the world -- can they be kept out of New Zealand? <STRONG>Philip Weinstein</STRONG> of the Ministry of Health thinks it's just a matter of time.

<P>Dengue fever, yellow fever, Ross River virus and others are spreading along with the mosquitoes that carry the diseases. Already potentially dangerous mosquitoes have been found in New Zealand and tourists arriving home from infected areas have brought new viruses into the country.

<P>&quot;Although the differing vector capabilities of local mosquitoes and the different climates in the Pacific and in New Zealand may partly account for the lack of transmission in New Zealand, a small virus pool and a lot of good luck are probably more significant factors. We were lucky that time, but what of the future?&quot;

<H2>Stormy Weather for Rainmakers</H2>

<P><STRONG>Steve Matthewman</STRONG> of Auckland University's Sociology Department shows that the contested case of weather modification is an interesting mix of science, pseudo-science and bad science.

<P>&quot;Praised as a project with significant potential to benefit mankind, and publicly reviled as the crime of the century in Pennsylvania, weather modification has elicited exaggerated praise and blame.&quot;

<P>Should we look to cloud seeding to boost depleted aquifers and help drought-stricken areas? Knowing the history and the science behind such efforts suggests the answer. 

<H2>Glowworm Man</H2>

<P>A 22-year-old post-grad from Massey University spends much of his time lurking in dark caves, wading through freezing water to film hundreds of hours of glowworm activity. <STRONG>Adam Broadley</STRONG> writes of his study of this curious creepy-crawly.

<H2>Under the Microscope</H2>

<P><CITE>Test your Psychic Powers</CITE> by Susan Blackmore and Adam Hart-Davis (Harper Collins 1995) gets the thumbs up from Professor Bernard Howard, the Secretary of the NZ Skeptics, as an interesting and informative book with useful tests and critical interpretations.

<P><CITE>The World Unfolds</CITE> series (Viking/Penguin 1995) of concertina-folded books provides a 1.5-metre look at skyscrapers, dinosaurs, the human body and aircraft. Something to keep the children - and may adults - quiet on a wet afternoon, says <CITE>NZSM</CITE> editor and reviewer Vicki Hyde.

<HR>

<H2>Where can I get it?</H2>

<P><CITE>NZ Science Monthly</CITE> is sold in the best bookshops. If your store doesn't have a copy, encourage them to order it! But remember, it's cheaper to <A href="subscrib.htm">subscribe...</A>

<P>

