<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>NZSM December/January 1995/96</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY TEXT="#000099" BGCOLOR="#ffffcc">
<A name="top"></A>
<H1><CITE><IMG SRC="../images/nzsmlogo.gif" height=66 width=240 ALIGN=top alt="New Zealand Science Monthly"></CITE> In the December/January issue:</H1>



<H2>Quick Dips and Over the Horizon</H2>

<UL>
<LI>Ball lightning caused by atmospheric vortices may explain UFO sightings.</LI>

<LI>The winning entry in this year's New Zealand Annual Micromouse Contest looked like a cross between Terminator 2 and something out of Doctor Who, and it blew away the local and international competitors.</LI>

<LI>How do you get a pair of identical twin birds? By the very rare event of having two yolks in a single egg. Identical twin emus in New Zealand are thought to be a world first for birdkind.</LI>

<LI>There's more to read -- finding a lost comet, solving the mystery of the New Zealand eel's sex life, and checking out the dangers of toxic algal blooms.</LI>
</UL>

<H2>Talking in Real Time</H2>

<P>There's good reason for the fast drone of the racing commentator -- it provides a linguistic means of making efficient use of memory resources, according to Canterbury University's <STRONG>Koenraad Kuiper</STRONG>.</P>

<P>Although talking is something we take for granted, it's actually a very complex business -- how <CITE>does</CITE> the brain keep up with someone who needs to say a lot very quickly? Race callers have to remember the names of the horses, how long the race is, the names of the jockeys and a whole host of other information which has to be recalled and spoken within a short space of time. In addition, the situation in a race can change dramatically within a very short period. Race commentators have to cope with this somehow (compare their situation to that of cricket commentators who sometimes have hours to describe play...)</P>

<P>Sports announcers have characteristic techniques that enable them to talk rapidly without stumbling, using formulae or set phrases ("and they're off!") to fill up the commentary without filling up the short-term memory; the monotone reduces the amount of processing needed in normal speech.</P>

<P>The speech used in slow sports does not have these properties. Formulae are used, but by no means exclusively. Intonation is frequently animated -- after all there isn't much else happening in a cricket game a lot of the time. Looking at the way the different sports announcers use speech tells us something about how the brain works.</P>

<H2>A Close-Up Look at Food</H2>

<P>Food researchers really like to see what they're eating, and Dairy Research Institute scientist <STRONG>Tony McKenna</STRONG> provides a look at how to look at food.

<P>A variety of sophisticated techniques allows researchers to gain a better idea of how foods are formed, behave and even taste by looking at how their basic components fit together.</P>

<P>McKenna freezes food, shatters it, embeds it in resin, coats it with gold or platinum and even zaps it with lasers to get the best idea of what is happening down in the depths of important dairy products, from cheese to ice cream.</P>

<H2>Spotlight</H2>

This month's Spotlight shines on the Southland Explorers Club and what these intrepid young explorers find combing the 26 kilometres of Oreti Beach, near Invercargill.

<H2>Under the Microscope</H2>

<P><CITE>Wrinkles in Time</CITE>, by George Smoot and Kay Davidson (Abacus/Penguin, $24.95) is a lively, well-written and non-technical account, warmly recommended by astronomer <STRONG>John Hearnshaw.</STRONG>

<P><CITE>Developing Ecotourism in New Zealand</CITE> by Julie Warren and C. Nicholas Taylor (SR&amp;D/Statistics New Zealand, $19.95) gets a mixed review from ecotourism operator <STRONG>Rodney Russ.</STRONG>

<P><CITE>Mineral Wealth of New Zealand</CITE> by Bruce Thompson, Bob Brathwaite and Tony Christie (IGNS, $49.95) is a colourful and well-presented technical resource book for the general audience, writes the <CITE>NZ Science Monthly's</CITE> <STRONG>Ros Davis.</STRONG>


<H3>And that's not all! See what you can come up with for the Picotaphs competition in our <STRONG>Neurobics</STRONG> puzzle column.</H3>

<HR>

<H2>Where can I get it?</H2>

<P><CITE>NZ Science Monthly</CITE> is sold in the best bookshops. If your store doesn't have a copy, encourage them to order it! But remember, it's cheaper to <A href="subscrib.htm">subscribe...</A>

<P>

