<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>NZSM Writers' Guidelines</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000099" BGCOLOR="#ffffcc">

<table width="100%">
<tr>
   <td width="84%"><H1><CITE><IMG SRC="../images/nzsmlogo.gif" height=66 width=240 ALIGN=top alt="NZ Science Monthly  "></CITE> Writers' Guidelines</H1></td>
   <td width="16%"><A HREF="../changes.htm">Last updated</A><BR>
      <!--Webber_Auto_StampDNR--><!--DS-->01-8-96<!----></td>
   </tr>
</table>

<P>The <CITE>New Zealand Science Monthly</CITE> provides an informative, readable 
look at New Zealand science and technology. Its readership is very 
diverse: Cabinet Ministers, secondary school pupils, university staff 
and students, top business management, researchers, engineers, farmers - anyone 
with an interest in science and technology in this country. 
</P>

<P>As such, we aim to explain clearly scientific research, technological 
developments and applications. In order to cover a broad range of 
topics, many of the items are brief. Space restrictions mean conciseness 
is valued. Footnotes and references are not required.
</P>

<P>At this stage, we are unable to offer payment for material, but welcome submissions. We're happy to receive copies of abstracts or conference presentations too.
</P>

Text can be:
<ul>
<li><A href="mailto:nzsm@spis.co.nz">e-mailed</A> to us</li>
<li>mailed in printed/typed form to P.O. Box 19-760, Christchurch</li>
<li>sent as ASCII text on an IBM-compatible disk (any size, will 
be returned if labelled)</li>
<li>faxed to us at: (03) 384-5138</li>
</ul>


<H3>The requirements for the different sections are:
</H3>

<P><STRONG>Quick Dips</STRONG>: short news items and information on research, technological 
developments and so on. One paragraph to ten (50-500 words). Accompanying 
photos or graphics most appreciated.
</P>

<P><STRONG>Over the Horizon</STRONG>: the same as Quick Dips only with an international 
connection - collaborative research, visiting researchers and 
suchlike.
</P>

<P><STRONG>Features</STRONG>: longer articles on scientific and technological items 
and issues. 500-3,000 words. Graphics appreciated.
</P>

<P><STRONG>Viewpoint</STRONG>: opinion pieces on issues that concern, interest or 
exasperate people involved in science and technology. 500-800 words.
</P>

<P><STRONG>Spotlight</STRONG>: profiles of or by individual researchers or teams, 
giving an idea of what it's like working as a researcher and why people 
get into it. This is aimed at giving readers a perception of scientists/technologists 
as people. 500-800 words, plus photo.
</P>

<P><STRONG>Under the Microscope</STRONG>: reviews of science or technology-related 
books, not necessarily New Zealand material. Information needed includes 
the name of the book, author/s or editor/s, publishers and date of 
publication, number of pages and NZ$ price. It should provide an opinion 
of the book, rather than just a pr&eacute;cis. 50-300 words.
</P>

<P><Strong>Discovery</strong>: pieces directly related to education at any level from primary to tertiary. 100-800 words.

<P><STRONG>Black Hole</STRONG>: a light-hearted look at any aspect of science and 
technology. 500-800 words, including a humorous bio sentence about 
the writer.
</P>

<P><STRONG>Graphics</STRONG>: photos, slides, graphs, charts, maps, cartoons, pictures 
and any other form of artwork. Graphics for all items are desired, 
and will be returned if requested and fully labelled.
</P>


