<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Weekly O'Press --  French Tryst Backgrounder</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=720>
<TR>
   <TD><IMG SRC="/spis/images/sambnr.gif" alt="Banner"></TD>
   <TD Align=left><H1><BIG>The Weekly O'Press</BIG></H1></TD>
   </TR>
<TR>
   <TD ALIGN=CENTER> L'&eacute;tat, c'est moi!</TD>
   </TR>
</TABLE>

<H1>Science and Politics Don't Mix Easily</H1>

<P>Politics and science can make uneasy bedfellows, particularly when a political agenda attempts to drive science. Much in all as politicians may want the world to work in the fashion that they decree, reality has a habit of catching up with them, sometimes with disastrous results. Millions and millions of people starved to death in the Soviet Union when the political machine attempted to drive the country's agricultural science. 

<P>In some cases, one might argue that there has been a certain ironic twist when political motives have suborned science: German chemist Fritz Haber, best known in New Zealand for his development of manufactured fertiliser, was also the head of Germany's 1920's poison gas programme. He lost his job when Hitler came to power, and was forced into exile for being Jewish, but the programme continued.

<P>Others have withstood the blandishments of politicians and recognised the need for a morality that rises above that of petty nationalism: last century Michael Faraday was asked by the British government to direct a poison gas project for use against the Russians in the Crimean War. He told them yes, the work was feasible, and no, he would have absolutely nothing to do with it.

<P>And then there was the attempt by the Arizona State legislature to simplify mathematics by redefining the constant <I>pi</i> as 3...

<P>

