<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Weekly O'Press -- Video Reviews</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=720>
<TR>
   <TD><IMG SRC="/spis/images/sambnr.gif" alt="Banner"></TD>
   <TD Align=left><H1><BIG>The Weekly O'Press</BIG></H1></TD>
   </TR>
<TR>
   <TD ALIGN=CENTER> L'&eacute;tat, c'est moi!</TD>
   </TR>
</TABLE>

<HR>

<H1>Video Reviews</H1>

<H3><CITE>The Day After</CITE>*</H3>

<P>It just goes to show what can happen when you let nuclear-related information run riot, and the explosive results cross national boundaries. However, the Americans just can't do grime, terror and hardship convincingly and this movie comes across like the cross between <CITE>The Waltons</CITE> and <CITE>The Longest Day</CITE>. If you get a chance, check out the much older, and much more believeably horrific <CITE>War Game</CITE> (commissioned by the BBC but never officially broadcast, as far as I am aware -- don't watch it if you're feeling depressed). Most environment groups and quality video stores should be able to point you toward a copy.
</P>
<H3><CITE>On The Beach</CITE>****</H3>

<P>Life's a beach, man. Well, it would be, wouldn't it, if you were left with nowhere to go but Australia? Just be thankful that you can admire a quality film and know that its particular plot line is far less likely than it once was.</P>

<H3><CITE>Cromwell</CITE> ****</H3>

<P>Some might say that Oliver Cromwell had the right idea when it came to royalty -- you might think that, but I couldn't possibly comment. This film paints a fairly sympathetic view of the Roundhead cause with Richard Harris playing the husky-voiced lead role. Alec Guiness is suitably spaniel-eyed as Charles I. It's no great loss when he goes to the block. History tells us what happened after that, and it doesn't say much for the radical republican approach to politics.

<H3><CITE>The Fugitive</CITE> *** (worth a run)</H3>

<P>Harrison Ford does well playing the typical sort of nice guy we've come to expect, in his role as The Fugitive, Dr Richard Kimble. He wouldn't kill his wife, nah. It was the guy with one arm who did it. And that's what Kimble spends the next 125 minutes trying to prove while on the dodge from Deputy US Marshall Sam Gerard (Tommy Lee Jones). It's a good solid movie with obligatory chase scenes (the forest, the sewer, the building, the parade), good acting and  not too silly a plot line.

<H2>More on movies</H2>

<P>LOTS more film reviews can be found at <A HREF="http://www.film.cam/film/">The Movie</A> web site.

<HR>

<H2>View <A HREF="/spis/sam.htm">Sam Bracanov's</A> activities in living 3D!</H2>

We've created a 3D autostereogram for your viewing pleasure. To see an autostereogram, relax and try to stare <EM>through</EM> the screen. After a time, the hidden image should float out of the background.

<P><A HREF="/spis/images/stereosa.gif"><IMG SRC="/spis/images/s_stereo.gif" ALT=[Sample] ALIGN=center></A> (41K)

<P><A HREF="/spis/pin.htm#SPIS">SPIS</A> makes <A HREF="/spis/stereogr.htm">custom autostereograms</A> on demand...

