<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Weekly O'Press -- French Nuclear Tryst Op-Ed</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=720>
<TR>
 <TD><IMG SRC="/spis/images/sambnr.gif" alt="Banner"></TD>
 <TD Align=left><H1><BIG>The Weekly O'Press</BIG></H1></TD>
 </TR>
<TR>
 <TD ALIGN=CENTER> L'&eacute;tat, c'est moi!</TD>
 </TR>
</TABLE>

<HR>

<H1>Op-Ed Page</H1>
<H3>By: Professor Geoff Stedman</H3>

<P><BIG>The Minister of Health has vetoed a proposed &quot;radiation discussion&quot; between
the French Ambassador, Jacques Le Blanc, and the Director of the
National Radiation Laboratory in Christchurch, Dr Andrew McEwan.</BIG>
</P>

<P>Now the public are right to be ultra-cautious of the supposed scientific
expert. There are a small proportion of physicists whose opinions I
certainly would not trust even within the appropriate specialty. (Is it
any different within any other profession or occupation?) Some experts
whom I know speak with arrogant complacency against the risks in nuclear
propulsion. That needs to be kept in balance. More importantly, the
far greater risks in petrol propulsion tend to be as firmly buried by
most of us.
</P>
<P>At the other end of the scale are still others who form a fixation and
drum up a pressure group ex nihilo: &quot;Would you allow <EM>your</EM> schoolgirl
daughter to be exposed to...&quot; whatever the speaker's latest hobby-horse
may be. It is great material for local community or parents' meetings.
It is guaranteed to fuel Luddite reaction against any change and (worst
of all) to blinker people into ignoring the major hazards of life.
</P>
<P>You can create an obsession, and most people have no sales resistance to
pseudoscientific lies. The media understandably love it and lionise the
provocative speaker. The simple and liberal insertion of subjunctives
can easily placate the responsibility for accurate journalism. The rest
of the profession sighs a deep sigh when a measured and informed reply
from a consensus view goes unreported.
</P>
<P>Dr McEwan certainly has had his share of such criticism. But I
would trust the Director of the National Radiation Laboratory, along
with the staff of the institutions this laboratory services, with
my life. Indeed, I have. And all New Zealanders have done so several
times over, as beneficiaries of many medically related services and
treatments during our life in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>The &quot;average person&quot; might well ask of any apparently controversial
scientific pronouncement: &quot;who can we believe?&quot; A satisfying answer is
not easy. But it has one guaranteed component: full discussion by all
parties. I will suggest a few more:
</P>

<UL>
<LI>avoid emotive arguments -- what are the facts?</LI>
<LI>what are <EM>all</EM> the facts?</LI>
<LI>what evidence is there on other counts that each contributor is trustworthy?</LI>
<LI>what is a clear consensus between such trustworthy speakers in this open debate?</LI></UL>

<P>The Minister's action is open to the interpretation that the first
of these at least is precisely what is to be forbidden in this case.
Maybe the Minister did not intend this; but I suggest the effect will
be the same for many New Zealanders. This, sadly, fuels a public
climate of suspicion for any informed comment on any technical issue,
such as any possible hazards with cell-phones. And this
interpretation, even if a misinterpretation, will be more probable
for European observers and for their reportage of the debate.
</P>
<P>I am sure that Dr McEwan is not even remotely pushing his own political
view (whatever it is, or is not) as a private citizen when he makes
public statements on Mururoa. He is not intruding some personal amoral
perspective on nuclear warfare. He does not intrude his own convictions as a private citizen at
all. He is acting in public as the cautious civil servant, the
well-informed spokesperson for his laboratory, for the national medical
administration, for New Zealand health care, for an international
consensus view among the cream of the world's specialists in
health-related nuclear issues. He is not straying outside the confines
of purely scientific comment.
</P>
<P>It bothers me that it is this one utterly independent aspect of the
matter which the Minister appears to want to suppress. Jack White
may not discuss matters with Andrew McEwan. Is there a fear that the
truth will out? It certainly will.
</P>
<P>These comments do not arise from any trace of support of nuclear testing
in principle, or of the French decisions on this. Quite the opposite.
I suggest that the real battleground, and where we should be
fighting, lies elsewhere. In focussing on, and in apparently
endeavouring to discredit, the politically unpalatable but accurate
comments of sober scientists the Minister is unwittingly placing a new
bomb into French hands: the possibility of revealing to the world the
gullibility for pseudoscience of the people of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>It is an ironic development. At the moment we might appear to be
winning the international debate, morally if not legally. The worst
thing we can do as a nation is to compromise the topic of debate. If we
as a people risk international exposure for barking up the wrong
tree, we risk the situation that nothing we say or do will count where
it matters.
</P>
<P>As citizens as well as scientists, all New Zealand scientists are bound
to be deeply concerned about the moral issues raised by all warfare,
especially the unspeakable horror of nuclear war. We are all
concerned that the French action, even over the limited period which
remains, will be used as a political precedent for testing -- or,
fearful thought, for warfare -- by other and perhaps many lesser powers
at a later date, whose environmental responsibility will be far less
than the French presently show.
</P>
<P>That, I suggest, is what we should be arguing. That is why the French
should stop now. Those are the battles worth fighting. They have
little to do with detailed scientific facts about the present tests. We
don't help anyone in these battles, least of all ourselves, by diverting
attention to issues which prove to be devoid of scientific credibility,
or by cultivating mistrust of a consensus of informed comment.
</P>
<P><I><A href="mailto:g.stedman@phys.canterbury.ac.nz">Geoff Stedman</A> is professor of the Department of Physics and Astronomy, University of Canterbury and President of the New Zealand Institute of Physics.</I>
</P>
<P><STRONG>Have your say by contributing to the Weekly O'Press <A HREF="/spis/samltrs.htm">Letters Page!</A>

<P>

