<HR>
<H1>Letters to the Editor</H1>

<H2>Re: French Radiation Tryst</H2>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR>

<TD VALIGN=TOP><H3>From: <A HREF = "mailto:nzsm@spis.co.nz">Vicki Hyde,</A> Editor, <A HREF="/spis/nzsm/nzsm.htm"><CITE>New Zealand Science Monthly</CITE></A></H3>
<P>I feel some sympathy for Dr Andrew McEwan of our country's National Radiation Laboratory. It's been his somewhat unenviable task to point out that arguing against the French testing on scientific grounds is untenable. Looked at rationally, it appears from the checking that has been done that an environmental catastrophe has not occurred in the past and is not likely to occur from the underground tests. Attempting to argue that the Pacific and its children are endangered by such tests is not likely to win a case in the World Court in the face of the evidence available.
</P>
<P>However, rationality is not the only response. One recent television advert which juxtaposes shots of children, an atmospheric bomb blast and a  dead fish washing up on the shore is designed to appeal much more to our hearts than our heads. It really irritates me because of the blatant emotional manipulation and misinformation it involves.
</P>
<P>Yet I have to confess that my own reactions are not that rational when it comes to nuclear weapons. I recall hearing the news of the Rainbow Warrior bombing courtesy of American Forces Radio (the only English-speaking radio station we could get while living in Japan). From that day on, I have tried not to buy French products -- and I was delighted when <CITE>New Scientist</CITE> recently suggested to their European readers that they try Australian and New Zealand vintages instead of French wines and champagne.
</P>
<P>Shortly after the bombing, I spoke to a UNESCO forum in Tokyo on environment and peace issues in the Pacific, and was startled to find how circumspect the response was. They didn't want to hear about the idea that an individual  moral stance could be transformed into political action which had implications for the international arena. (Later reflection suggested that the quick change of subject probably had something to do with the uncomfortable awareness of the country's toothless non-nuclear constitution and its probable daily violation by US forces in Japan.)
</P>
<P>Rather than trying to use scientific justifications -- which may be equivocal at best -- we should acknowledge that our anger and contempt concerning the resumed testing arises from a deep-seated moral repugnance at what such testing represents. And there's nothing wrong with that.
</P>
<H1>J'accuse!
</H1>
</TD>
<TD><P><IMG SRC="/spis/images/letters.gif">Have your say -- write to the <A HREF="mailto:opress@spis.co.nz">editor</A> now!</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<H2>Re: Where on EARTH is Sam Bracanov? <A HREF="/spis/sam.htm">(October 30th)</A></H2>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP><H3>From: <A HREF="mailto:young.wn.planet.gen.nz">Hugh Young,</A> Porirua</H3>
<P>It is incredible that in this day and age, someone can be hailed into court and required to sign a good-behaviour bond or go to gaol, xon the basis that they *might* commit a crime. That is not how our justice system is supposed to work.
<P>And such a crime! To spray air-freshener in the general direction of someone, deary me! This quasi-religious solicitousness for royal personages takes us back to the 1950s, if not the 1600s. Let the police protect Elizabeth Windsor from people who wish her harm, not persecute those who *might* be rude to her with "natural, pine-scented fragrance".</TD>

<TD VALIGN=TOP><H3>From: <A HREF="mailto:lachlan@actrix.gen.nz">Peter McLachlan</A> </H3>
<P>Regarding Sam the Stirrer.

<P>If he is not a naturalised Newzealander, the athourities could pesumeably
invite him to depart for " Bosnia " ? If he has taken the oath of allegiance,
perhaps he should be asked to adhere to it,or again depart for his country of
birth.
</TD>

<TD><P><IMG SRC="/spis/images/letters.gif">Have your say -- write to the <A HREF="mailto:opress@spis.co.nz">editor</A> now!</TD>
</TABLE>

