<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Climbing Out on the Web</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#ccffff">
<IMG SRC="images/climbw1.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=322 HEIGHT=180 alt="Woman on web, 2K">
<table>
<tr>
   <td ALIGN=LEFT><H1>Climbing Out<br>on the Web</H1><br><H2><I>A primer for people considering<br>their own web site</I></h2></td>
   <td width="16%"><A HREF="changes.htm">Last updated</A><BR>
      <!--Webber_Auto_StampDNR--><!--DS-->July 14, 1996<!----></td>
   </tr>
</table>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><SMALL><STRONG>Note:</STRONG> This unified version is suitable for printing from your browser or browsing off-line.</SMALL>


<P><TABLE width="100%">
<TR>
   <TD ><A HREF="#What">What is the Web?</A><BR>...and who uses it</TD>
   <TD><A HREF="#Applications">Web Applications</A></TD>
   <TD><A  HREF="#Sites">Site</A> and  <A HREF="#Resources">Resource</A> Lists</TD>
   </TR>
<TR>
   <TD><A HREF="#You">You and the Web</A><BR>...the benefits of your own site</TD>
   <TD><A HREF="#Promotion">Web Site Promotion</A></TD>
   <TD><A HREF="#Service">NZ Web Service Providers</A></TD>
   </TR>
<TR>
   <TD><A  HREF="#Design">Web Site Design</A><br>...doing it <STRONG>right</STRONG></TD>
   <TD><A  HREF="#Security">Security and Electronic Commerce</A></TD>
   <TD><A HREF="#Here">Here's the Pitch</A></TD>
   </TR>
</TABLE>

<HR>
<A NAME="What"></A>
<H1>What is the Web?</H1>
<I>If you're already familiar with the Web, <A href="#Who">skip the introduction.</A></I>

<P>The World Wide Web is a popular and fairly recent extension of the Internet, the global electronic communications network. Information is presented on "pages" made accessible through programs called Web browsers.
</P>
<P><I>Common browsers include <A HREF="http://home.netscape.com">Netscape</A>, <A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/SDG/Software/Mosaic/NCSAMosaicHome.html">Mosaic</A> and <A HREF="http://www.jackson.freenet.org/about_lynx/www_start.html">Lynx</A>.
</I></P>
<P>The information provided reflects the activities, interests and, frequently, <A HREF="people.htm#Peter">personality</A> of those who host the pages -- from <A HREF="sca.htm">recreation</A> and research areas through to <A HREF="http://www.etext.org/Zines/Quanta/">full-blown publications</A>, <A HREF=" http://www.cezanne.com/eng/accueil.html">art galleries</A> and <A HREF="http://cc.lut.fi/~mega/jukebox.html ">sound studios</A>.
</P>
<P>Web pages are usually designed so that the reader can effortlessly follow "links" to related subjects, information or files. The links could be pointing to somewhere else on the <A HREF="climwhat.htm#Design">same page</A> or <A HREF="http://www.joes.com/home/spis_ltd">half a world</A> away.
</P>
<A NAME="Who"><H2>Who is using the Web?</H2></A>
<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD><P>Exact usage numbers are impossible to determine, but an indication can be gained from the following:
</P>
<P>Over the past two years, the number of Web pages on-line has grown from just a few thousand to an estimated 20 million or more. In New Zealand alone, a recent listing contained more than 45,000 pages;  an estimate published just one month earlier suggested 20,000.
</P>
<P>The number and range of people who read Web pages is also increasing dramatically -- from an estimated 250,000 in June 1994 to 30 million today.
</P></TD>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="images/climgr1.gif" HEIGHT=226 WIDTH=180 alt="Domain name growth (2K)"><BR>
<SMALL><I>Growth in total and commercial registered "domain names" in New Zealand (the number of sites is considerably larger than this)<BR><STRONG>.co </STRONG>= commercial sites</I></SMALL></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD><P>In the beginning, the main users and authors were academic (reflecting the origins of the Internet), but now the trend is towards wider involvement from companies, societies and private individuals.
</P>
<P>There is still a reasonably high cost involved in using the Web, so readers are likely to be:
</P>
<UL><LI> professionals whose employers are footing the bill</LI>
<LI> businesses seeking out critical information or trading opportunities
</LI>
<LI>individuals in the middle- to upper-income bands who can afford
not only the necessary hardware, but also the connection and on-line fees
</LI></UL>
<P>This picture too is changing, as costs continue to decrease. In New Zealand over the past few months, international data transfer charges have halved (from $10/MB to $5/MB), opening up the Web to more users.
</P>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="images/climgr2.gif" HEIGHT=145 WIDTH=238 alt="Domain name breakdown (2K)"><BR><SMALL><I>Breakdown of domains by type<BR>November 1995</I></SMALL></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<HR SIZE="5">
<A NAME="You"><H1>You and the Web</H1></A>
<H2>What can a Web site do for me?</H2>
Web sites are typically created to serve one or more of these purposes:
<UL>
<LI>information: providing a service to specific groups or to all-comers
</LI>
<LI>communication: publishing news items and circulars or promoting dialogue on issues of interest to the host
</LI>
<LI>promotion: giving a good impression of the sites owner, and their activities and possibly extending into electronic commerce
</LI>
</UL>
<I><A href="climweb.htm#Electronic">Electronic commerce</A> is trade where payments are sent electronically (e.g. over the Web).</I>

<P>The following table covers the kinds of information, promotion and communication activities likely to be carried out by different site hosts:
</P>
<P><TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TH></TH><TH>Individual</TH><TH>Organisation</TH><TH>Company</TH></TR>
<TR>
  <TH>Information</TH>
  <TD><A HREF="people.htm#Nick">Personal interests and hobbies</A><BR>Favourite links<BR>Personal projects</TD>
  <TD>Reports on past activities<BR>Officer directory<BR>Membership directory<BR>Library/resource lists<BR>Searchable back-issues or index of publications<BR>Awards, grants and fellowships<BR>Links to related organisations and sites</TD>
   <TD><A HREF="softserv.htm#MediaMonitor">Product descriptions</A><BR>Technical information<BR>New releases<BR>Annual reports<BR><A HREF="pin.htm">Links to industry partners and associations</A></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
   <TH>Communication</TH>
   <TD>Circulars<BR>Personal email link<BR><A HREF="#ForMore">Other contact information</A></TD>
   <TD>Upcoming events<BR>Requests for discussion<BR>Membership feedback<BR><A HREF="mailto:climb@spis.co.nz">Email links</A> to officers and staff</TD>
   <TD>Customer feedback<BR><A HREF="samvote.htm">Surveys</A> and focus groups<BR>Press releases<BR>Crisis management<BR>Email links to key personnel<BR>Customer service</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
  <TH>Promotion</TH>
  <TD><A HREF="http://agtv-pc11.massey.ac.nz/centres/cprr/postgrad/peterj/peterpg.htm">CV</A><BR>Examples of work (e.g. graphic art, software, writing)<BR>Links to former employers</TD>
  <TD><A HREF="skeptics.htm">Organisation aims, supporters and achievements</A><BR>Public events and competitions<BR>Requests for public support or lobbying</TD>
  <TD><A HREF="pin.htm#SPIS">Company information</A><BR>Major clients<BR><A HREF="services.htm">Product and service catalogues</A><BR>Samples and free offers<BR>Electronic commerce</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P></P>
<H2>What are the limitations?
</H2>
<P>A broad range of information and services can be provided on the Web, but there are both limitations and drawbacks, and these should be weighed when considering your own Web site:
</P>
<UL>
<LI><STRONG>access</STRONG><BR>
There is not much point establishing a site if the people you want to reach do not have or do not plan to get Web access.<BR>
<I>On the other hand, you may be able to expand your reach to include new contacts, clients or members who find your offerings interesting.</I>
</LI>
<LI><A href="#Promotion"><STRONG>getting attention</STRONG></A><BR>
With over 20 million pages out there already, you have to do something really different if you want to <A href="#Promotion">make an impact</A> in the Web community itself.<BR>
<I>Nonetheless, in recent months, two New Zealand sites have been listed among the <A HREF="http://icair.iac.org.nz">top 5%</A> of sites visited worldwide.</I>
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>bandwidth constraints</STRONG><BR>
<I>Bandwidth relates to the amount of data which can be sent over communication links</I><BR>
The tremendous growth in Web usage has resulted in slowdowns (or "brownouts") in certain parts of the world, especially the US. Links to and from some overseas sites can be very slow at peak times. If this trend continues, people will be dissuaded from using the Web.
<BR>
<I>At present within New Zealand, there appears to be little problem with this.
</I>
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>costs</STRONG><BR>
Although a Web site can be set up fairly economically by renting space from a <A HREF="#Service">service provider</A>, you still have to bear the costs of all accesses to your pages by readers. If your readers are within New Zealand, this can be quite cheap, or even free. Visitors from outside New Zealand will cost you, however.<BR>
<I>If you have a popular site, these charges can rapidly become a major issue!</I>
</LI>

<LI><A HREF="#Security"><STRONG>security</STRONG></A><BR>
If you are merely providing information which is free to all, this will not be a problem. But if you are collecting or providing information which you want to protect or restrict in some way (including personal information, finance and copyrighted material), security can become an issue.
</LI>
</UL>
<HR SIZE="5">
<A NAME="Design"><H1>Web Site Design</H1></A>
<H2>The Basics</H2>
<P>Web pages are created using a simple language called "HTML"  which describes the structure and contents of your offering. HTML provides some control over page layout, as well as the ability to add images, tables, forms and even animations and sound (though not all browsers will be able to make use of this).
</P>
<I>While HTML (HyperText Markup Language) allows authors to structure information for presentation, it does not define how pages will actually appear -- that is up to each browser and its user settings.</I>
<P>Having your own Web page can be as simple as finding a <A HREF="#Service">service provider</A> to rent you the storage space and Web connection, then creating your page.
</P>
<P>More complex sites, such as those with <A HREF="#Applications">database and indexing</A> capabilities or extensive sound and graphics, require careful programming and testing to deliver the desired results.
</P>
<P>Most sites need ongoing maintenance. A page rapidly <A HREF="sam.htm">goes stale</A> if it is not updated. Links on the page may no longer be valid, or the information itself may become out of date.
</P>
<P>Web sites tend to grow over time as pages are added to cover new subjects or activities. If you're not careful, the whole structure can become unwieldy. Good site planning and design allows you to forestall this, so be sure to put the time in early on to decide how the growth will be managed.
</P>
<H2>Doing it Right
</H2>
<P>Putting up Web pages is just a new form of publishing, subject to most of the old conventions, plus a few new wrinkles. Good offerings have useful content, clear presentation and consistent style  and can be read with most or all of the different browsers in use. Bad ones are browser-specific, have little or no content or simply represent somebody going on-line to say "me too"
</P>
<P>The Web itself contains a large number of <A HREF="#Resources">guides</A> on how to create Web pages. Some will tell you the latest tricks to make your favourite browser display pages to the best effect. Others will give you clear indications of what is and isn't good style and design, and will usually reinforce the following message:
</P>
<P>If you want your page to be read by others, bear in mind that they won't all be using the same browser, or even the same kind of computer.
</P>
<P>Tricks and illusions created to impress users of one popular browser may look sad -- or even ridiculous -- if read by another. If the purpose of your pages is to convey information, then learn and use standard HTML. If the purpose is to dazzle, then be aware that not every visitor will be dazzled -- and some will be annoyed.
</P>
<H2>Validate, Validate, Validate!
</H2>
<P>Once a Web page has been created, it is important that it be checked out as correct HTML. It is all too easy to make a mistake in page creation which works on your test browser, but results in gibberish on the one used by your next visitor.
</P>
<P>Fortunately, both <A HREF="#Resources">software and Web sites</A> exist which will perform this vital validation function for you. Use them!
</P>
<H2>Using Graphics
</H2>
<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD><P>Many Web pages can be enhanced by judicious use of <A HREF="http://www.fn.net/gifs/">graphics</A>
-- the key word is <STRONG>judicious</STRONG>. When people are paying to look at your page (and most are, even if you are picking up some of the cost), they don't want to receive a 100KB  graphic to embellish 100 words of text (there are <A HREF="images/12goats.gif">exceptions</A>, of course).
</P>
<P>Many readers set their browsers up to ignore all images, so it is important that you design your pages so that they are attractive and usable even if the graphics are not present or, worse, replaced by little "image here" boxes as some browsers do.
</P>
</TD>
<TD Align=Center>
<SMALL><I>Original image:</I></SMALL><BR><A HREF="wop.htm">
<IMG SRC="images/sambnr.gif" alt="Weekly O'Press banner (2K)" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=120></A><BR>
<SMALL><I>becomes...</I></SMALL><BR>
<IMG SRC="images/imaghere.gif" alt="Netscape image placeholder (.3K)" WIDTH=36  HEIGHT=37><BR>
<SMALL><I>"Image here"</I></SMALL>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>Good Web page designers use a number of techniques to reduce the size and increase the viewing speed of the graphics they use, and to blend them into the overall design and layout of the page. These include:
<UL>
<LI>Store an image with no more colours than it requires (this can cut file sizes by a factor of five!)</LI>
<LI>Always specify the image dimensions (with some browsers, this makes a page load faster)</LI>
<LI>Usually, save an image with a <A href="http://dragon.jpl.nasa.gov/~adam/transparent.html">transparent</A> background so it blends in with the page background</LI>
<LI>Images <I>without</I> transparent backgrounds can be saved in "interlaced" format to make apparent loading time faster</LI>
</UL>
<P><I>An "interlaced" image is loaded and displayed in <A HREF="images/12goats.gif">multiple passes</A> -- the first pass gives a rough idea of what it looks like, and the remaining ones fill in the detail.</I>
</P>
<HR>
<A NAME="Applications"></A>
<H1>Web Applications</H1>
<P>Web pages are often used to present or collect information for databases. Sometimes this kind of application is solely for in-house use, with Web tools used but without the data being available on the World Wide Web itself.
</P>
<P>Typical database publishing applications include:
</P>
<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>
<UL>
<LI>product catalogues</LI>
<LI>publication indices</LI>
<LI>search and retrieval of articles and documents</LI>
<LI>policy documents</LI>
<LI>technical information</LI>
<LI>procedure manuals</LI>
<LI>real estate listings</LI>
<LI>directories of all kinds</LI>
</UL></TD>
<TD rowspan=2><SMALL><I>Output example from an on-line database:</I></SMALL><BR><IMG SRC="images/spisinfo.gif" alt="Web Developers' Consortium listing (8K)" WIDTH=464  HEIGHT=544>
    </TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD>
<P>Typical Web data collection applications include:</P>
<UL>
<LI>feedback and survey forms</LI>
<LI>order placement</LI>
<LI>service requests</LI>
<LI>application forms</LI>
<LI>contact information</LI>
<LI>competitions and games</LI>
</UL>
<P><SMALL><I>Data collection example:</I></SMALL><BR><IMG SRC="images/collect.gif" alt="Classified ad entry (2K)" WIDTH=400  HEIGHT=134></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>For both data publishing and data collection, some programming support is usually required to support the application. Although there are ways to collect data from Web page forms without programming, this rapidly becomes unwieldy as the amount of data increases.
</P>
<P>Using a protocol known as CGI, Web applications are able to transfer data to and from Web pages and forms. This information is usually stored in databases on the server machine -- a well-designed Web application will not require a change in the format or the layout of existing databases you may already be using.
</P>
<P><I>A server is the computer on which the Web site or application is stored.
</I>

<P>The programming language used to develop a Web application will generally vary depending on the nature of the server machine (e.g. Unix-based, Windows-based), but will most commonly be Perl, C, <A HREF="softserv.htm#Programming">Delphi</A>, Visual Basic or a dedicated add-on to a database management system.
</P>
<P>Because of the programming requirements, developing Web applications generally requires a distinct set of skills from those which go into Web page design. It is important to remember this when deciding who will create your site.
</P>
<P>The best Web site developers are those who are able to marry the <A HREF="#Here">divergent disciplines</A> of professional publishing, graphic design and software engineering.
</P>

<HR SIZE="5">

<A NAME="Promotion">
<H1>Web Site Promotion
</H1></A>
<P>Creating a Web site is only half the story. If your site is to to serve any purpose, people must know that it is there. Two audiences are usually targeted:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>your natural audience (e.g. members, clients or subscribers) who may have Web access, or be getting it soon</LI>
<LI>the wider Web community, who use the <A HREF="#Lycos">search and indexing</A> services on the Web to find pages with information of interest to them</LI>
</UL>
<P>The first group is usually easy enough to reach through your existing lines of communication.
</P>
<P>You will usually have to go to some trouble to explain the purpose and benefits of the Web-based service to those who are not yet "Web aware", in the hope that they will find your site one of many reasons to get a connection themselves.
</P>
<H2>Making a splash on the Web
</H2>
<P>Reaching Web readers at large is more difficult, particularly when you're competing with 20 million other pages. You should:
</P>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD>
<UL>
<LI><STRONG>list your site in the Web catalogues</STRONG><BR>
Don't try to get on them all -- pick the ones which most closely match your site. Logical places to start would be indices which focus on your location (Christchurch, New Zealand, Oceania, Asia) or the main contents of your site (science, software, publishing, humour, skeptics, medi&aelig;val recreation).</LI>
</UL>
</TD><TD VALIGN=TOP><SMALL><I>A page from the Lycos on-line search engine:</I></SMALL><BR>
<IMG SRC="images/lycos.gif" alt="Lycos main screen (8K)" WIDTH=583 HEIGHT=276>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<UL>
<LI><STRONG>distribute press releases</STRONG><BR>
Send out press releases not just to those publications in your field, but also to the computer pages of local papers and Net-oriented magazines, especially if your site has something different to offer. Follow these up with new releases whenever you make a significant addition or improvement.
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>develop your site on an on-going basis</STRONG><BR>
Many pages are worth visiting once. Few are worth a second look unless the host makes an effort to keep them up-to-date and interesting. New links, ideas and points of interest are essential.
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>add your web address to all stationery, printed and electronic</STRONG><BR>
Any place you list your contact information, make sure to add your Web address too. This means on your letterheads, business cards, publication mastheads, email sigs -- anywhere people would expect to see it.<BR>
<I>A sig (signature)  is a tailpiece on email messages which usually contains your email address.</I>
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>add in links to compatible sites</STRONG><BR>
Mutual links between your site and others in a related area will help bring visitors interested in what you do, and your link will do the same for them.</LI>
<LI><STRONG>promote your site on relevant newsgroups</STRONG><BR>
You <I>must</I> do this appropriately, following the often tricky conventions of netiquette if you are to succeed. Inappropriate promotion can hinder rather than boost your sites popularity.<BR>
<I>Netiquette is a set of courtesy conventions designed to promote efficient, reasonable and hassle-free use of the Internet.</I>
</LI>
</UL>

<HR SIZE="5">

<A NAME="Security">
<H1>Security and Electronic Commerce
</H1></A>
<H2>Web Security
</H2>
<P>This is an area which is still developing rapidly, and there are no guaranteed solutions. Security concerns are threefold:
</P>
<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD>
<UL>
<LI><STRONG>system security</STRONG><BR>
This is mainly a concern for service providers and organisations with their own servers. Because there are ways for Web applications to modify the data on the machines on which they are run, there is always the possibility that unauthorised access and modification can occur through program design flaws or deliberate intent.
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>confidentiality</STRONG><BR>
Any Web usage that involves sensitive data (e.g. personal information, credit card details, technical data) needs to be protected against unauthorised access and eavesdropping. This is difficult when the information passed between the reader and the Web server can be routed through intermediate hosts on the Internet. Access restrictions using passwords and data encryption are two of the most common approaches to providing protection in this area.
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>authentication</STRONG><BR>
In the Web world, there is no straightforward way of knowing who is reading a page or filling out a form. This can be a severe limitation, especially in the commercial arena.
</LI>
</UL>
</TD>
<TD><SMALL><I>Example of a passworded gateway:</I></SMALL><BR>
<IMG SRC="images/lock.gif" alt="Password prompt (3K)" WIDTH=424 HEIGHT=219>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<A NAME="Electronic">
<H2>Electronic commerce
</H2></A>
<P>Because of the security concerns noted above, and the critical fact that money is involved, electronic commerce on the Web is more complex than almost any other activity.
</P>
<P>At present, most commercial transactions that arise from the Web are carried on outside it, but this is slowly changing. Corporations like Mastercard and Visa are devising strategies for adding the security and confidence necessary to make transactions over the Web an everyday occurrence.
</P>
<P>There is no need to wait for them, however. Even as the paragraph above was being written, we received confirmation of a <A HREF="http://super.sonic.net/ann/delphi/more/tcompres/">software</A> sale which relied on the <A HREF="#FV">First Virtual</A> Internet Payment System (FV). Their system is a good example of what is possible at present:
</P>
<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD>
<UL>
<LI>suppliers and potential buyers pay a small fee to be registered with FV</LI>
<LI>potential buyers also provide their credit card details via a secure route to FV, who gives them an FV identification number (ID)
</LI>
<LI>when a buyer sees something they want, they transmit their ID (but <I>not</I> any credit card information) to the supplier, who passes that on to FV
</LI>
<LI>FV then emails the buyer requesting authorisation --  the transaction is carried out only if this is received. Thus, anyone who obtains the buyers ID must also be able to intercept and respond to email directed at the buyer if they want to use it fraudulently.
</LI>
<LI>when authorisation is received, FV processes a credit card transaction
billing the buyer (and paying FV)
</LI>
<LI>at regular intervals, FV credits all payments (less a small transaction fee) to the suppliers nominated account
</LI>
<LI>Note that there is always a risk that the buyer will refuse to authorise the transaction, even though they have received the goods (or information). Naturally, anyone doing this too often is expelled from the system.
</LI></UL></TD>
<TD><SMALL><I>First Virtual's Welcome screen:</I></SMALL><BR>
<IMG SRC="images/fv.gif" alt="First Virtual main screen (4K)" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=224>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>Other systems aiming to provide electronic transactions are already operating, and experiments are under way on the next generation of electronic transactions, including <A HREF="#Resources">"cybercash"</A>.
</P>
<P>There are simpler solutions, of course -- such as providing an order form for your readers to print out and fax, or supporting telephone sales (<A HREF="mailto:climb@spis.co.nz">"email</A> us your phone number and we'll contact you").
</P>
