<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Climbing Out on the Web -- Web Applications</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#ccffff">
<A NAME="Applications"></A>
<IMG SRC="images/climbw1.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=322 HEIGHT=180 alt="Woman on web, 2K">
<table>
<tr>
   <td ALIGN=LEFT><H1>Web Applications</H1></td>
   <td width="16%"><A HREF="changes.htm">Last updated</A><BR>
      <!--Webber_Auto_StampDNR--><!--DS-->4-12-95<!----></td>
   </tr>
</table>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>Web pages are often used to present or collect information for databases. Sometimes this kind of application is solely for in-house use, with Web tools used but without the data being available on the World Wide Web itself.
</P>
<P>Typical database publishing applications include:
</P>
<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>
<UL>
<LI>product catalogues</LI>
<LI>publication indices</LI>
<LI>search and retrieval of articles and documents</LI>
<LI>policy documents</LI>
<LI>technical information</LI>
<LI>procedure manuals</LI>
<LI>real estate listings</LI>
<LI>directories of all kinds</LI>
</UL></TD>
<TD rowspan=2><SMALL><I>Output example from an on-line database:</I></SMALL><BR><IMG SRC="images/spisinfo.gif" alt="Web Developers' Consortium listing (8K)" WIDTH=464  HEIGHT=544>
    </TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD>
<P>Typical Web data collection applications include:</P>
<UL>
<LI>feedback and survey forms</LI>
<LI>order placement</LI>
<LI>service requests</LI>
<LI>application forms</LI>
<LI>contact information</LI>
<LI>competitions and games</LI>
</UL>
<P><SMALL><I>Data collection example:</I></SMALL><BR><IMG SRC="images/collect.gif" alt="Classified ad entry (2K)" WIDTH=400  HEIGHT=134></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>For both data publishing and data collection, some programming support is usually required to support the application. Although there are ways to collect data from Web page forms without programming, this rapidly becomes unwieldy as the amount of data increases.
</P>
<P>Using a protocol known as CGI, Web applications are able to transfer data to and from Web pages and forms. This information is usually stored in databases on the server machine -- a well-designed Web application will not require a change in the format or the layout of existing databases you may already be using.
</P>
<P><I>A server is the computer on which the Web site or application is stored.
</I>

<P>The programming language used to develop a Web application will generally vary depending on the nature of the server machine (e.g. Unix-based, Windows-based), but will most commonly be Perl, C, <A HREF="softserv.htm#Programming">Delphi</A>, Visual Basic or a dedicated add-on to a database management system.
</P>
<P>Because of the programming requirements, developing Web applications generally requires a distinct set of skills from those which go into Web page design. It is important to remember this when deciding who will create your site.
</P>
<P>The best Web site developers are those who are able to marry the <A HREF="climsite.htm#Here">divergent disciplines</A> of professional publishing, graphic design and software engineering.
</P>

<HR SIZE="5">

<A NAME="Promotion">
<H1>Web Site Promotion
</H1></A>
<P>Creating a Web site is only half the story. If your site is to to serve any purpose, people must know that it is there. Two audiences are usually targeted:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>your natural audience (e.g. members, clients or subscribers) who may have Web access, or be getting it soon</LI>
<LI>the wider Web community, who use the <A HREF="climsite.htm#Lycos">search and indexing</A> services on the Web to find pages with information of interest to them</LI>
</UL>
<P>The first group is usually easy enough to reach through your existing lines of communication.
</P>
<P>You will usually have to go to some trouble to explain the purpose and benefits of the Web-based service to those who are not yet "Web aware", in the hope that they will find your site one of many reasons to get a connection themselves.
</P>
<H2>Making a splash on the Web
</H2>
<P>Reaching Web readers at large is more difficult, particularly when you're competing with 20 million other pages. You should:
</P>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD>
<UL>
<LI><STRONG>list your site in the Web catalogues</STRONG><BR>
Don't try to get on them all -- pick the ones which most closely match your site. Logical places to start would be indices which focus on your location (Christchurch, New Zealand, Oceania, Asia) or the main contents of your site (science, software, publishing, humour, skeptics, medi&aelig;val recreation).</LI>
</UL>
</TD><TD VALIGN=TOP><SMALL><I>A page from the Lycos on-line search engine:</I></SMALL><BR>
<IMG SRC="images/lycos.gif" alt="Lycos main screen (8K)" WIDTH=583 HEIGHT=276>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<UL>
<LI><STRONG>distribute press releases</STRONG><BR>
Send out press releases not just to those publications in your field, but also to the computer pages of local papers and Net-oriented magazines, especially if your site has something different to offer. Follow these up with new releases whenever you make a significant addition or improvement.
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>develop your site on an on-going basis</STRONG><BR>
Many pages are worth visiting once. Few are worth a second look unless the host makes an effort to keep them up-to-date and interesting. New links, ideas and points of interest are essential.
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>add your web address to all stationery, printed and electronic</STRONG><BR>
Any place you list your contact information, make sure to add your Web address too. This means on your letterheads, business cards, publication mastheads, email sigs -- anywhere people would expect to see it.<BR>
<I>A sig (signature)  is a tailpiece on email messages which usually contains your email address.</I>
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>add in links to compatible sites</STRONG><BR>
Mutual links between your site and others in a related area will help bring visitors interested in what you do, and your link will do the same for them.</LI>
<LI><STRONG>promote your site on relevant newsgroups</STRONG><BR>
You <I>must</I> do this appropriately, following the often tricky conventions of netiquette if you are to succeed. Inappropriate promotion can hinder rather than boost your sites popularity.<BR>
<I>Netiquette is a set of courtesy conventions designed to promote efficient, reasonable and hassle-free use of the Internet.</I>
</LI>
</UL>

<HR SIZE="5">

<A NAME="Security">
<H1>Security and Electronic Commerce
</H1></A>
<H2>Web Security
</H2>
<P>This is an area which is still developing rapidly, and there are no guaranteed solutions. Security concerns are threefold:
</P>
<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD>
<UL>
<LI><STRONG>system security</STRONG><BR>
This is mainly a concern for service providers and organisations with their own servers. Because there are ways for Web applications to modify the data on the machines on which they are run, there is always the possibility that unauthorised access and modification can occur through program design flaws or deliberate intent.
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>confidentiality</STRONG><BR>
Any Web usage that involves sensitive data (e.g. personal information, credit card details, technical data) needs to be protected against unauthorised access and eavesdropping. This is difficult when the information passed between the reader and the Web server can be routed through intermediate hosts on the Internet. Access restrictions using passwords and data encryption are two of the most common approaches to providing protection in this area.
</LI>
<LI><STRONG>authentication</STRONG><BR>
In the Web world, there is no straightforward way of knowing who is reading a page or filling out a form. This can be a severe limitation, especially in the commercial arena.
</LI>
</UL>
</TD>
<TD><SMALL><I>Example of a passworded gateway:</I></SMALL><BR>
<IMG SRC="images/lock.gif" alt="Password prompt (3K)" WIDTH=424 HEIGHT=219>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<A NAME="Electronic">
<H2>Electronic commerce
</H2></A>
<P>Because of the security concerns noted above, and the critical fact that money is involved, electronic commerce on the Web is more complex than almost any other activity.
</P>
<P>At present, most commercial transactions that arise from the Web are carried on outside it, but this is slowly changing. Corporations like Mastercard and Visa are devising strategies for adding the security and confidence necessary to make transactions over the Web an everyday occurrence.
</P>
<P>There is no need to wait for them, however. Even as the paragraph above was being written, we received confirmation of a <A HREF="http://super.sonic.net/ann/delphi/more/tcompres/">software</A> sale which relied on the <A HREF="climsite.htm#FV">First Virtual</A> Internet Payment System (FV). Their system is a good example of what is possible at present:
</P>
<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD>
<UL>
<LI>suppliers and potential buyers pay a small fee to be registered with FV</LI>
<LI>potential buyers also provide their credit card details via a secure route to FV, who gives them an FV identification number (ID)
</LI>
<LI>when a buyer sees something they want, they transmit their ID (but <I>not</I> any credit card information) to the supplier, who passes that on to FV
</LI>
<LI>FV then emails the buyer requesting authorisation --  the transaction is carried out only if this is received. Thus, anyone who obtains the buyers ID must also be able to intercept and respond to email directed at the buyer if they want to use it fraudulently.
</LI>
<LI>when authorisation is received, FV processes a credit card transaction
billing the buyer (and paying FV)
</LI>
<LI>at regular intervals, FV credits all payments (less a small transaction fee) to the suppliers nominated account
</LI>
<LI>Note that there is always a risk that the buyer will refuse to authorise the transaction, even though they have received the goods (or information). Naturally, anyone doing this too often is expelled from the system.
</LI></UL></TD>
<TD><SMALL><I>First Virtual's Welcome screen:</I></SMALL><BR>
<IMG SRC="images/fv.gif" alt="First Virtual main screen (4K)" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=224>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>Other systems aiming to provide electronic transactions are already operating, and experiments are under way on the next generation of electronic transactions, including <A HREF="climsite.htm#Resources">"cybercash"</A>.
</P>
<P>There are simpler solutions, of course -- such as providing an order form for your readers to print out and fax, or supporting telephone sales (<A HREF="mailto:climb@spis.co.nz">"email</A> us your phone number and we'll contact you").
</P>
<P>
