<HTML>
<HEAD>
<!-- Copyright © 1996, South Pacific Information Services Ltd, All Rights Reserved -->
<TITLE>SPIS Webview Offline Web Browser -- Options</TITLE>
</HEAD>   
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#ccffff">
<table width="100%">
<tr>
 <td ALIGN=CENTER><H1>SPIS Webview</H1>
<H2><I>Optional Features</I></H2></td>
  <TD><IMG SRC="images/webview.gif" ALIGN=LEFT alt="Logo"></TD>
</tr>
</TABLE>
<P>From v2.5 onwards, Webview includes several optional features of particular interest to those using it for offline demonstrations, training, web site simulation and data gathering. The evaluation version of Webview has all the optional features <B>active</B> so you can try them out. However, you must specifically order each option if you want it to be usable in the <A HREF="webview.htm#Registration">registered</A> version.
<A NAME="Options"></A>
<P>The optional features are:
<P><UL>
 <LI><A HREF="#Editor">Built-in Editor</A>
 <LI><A HREF="#Scripts">Scripted Demonstrations</A>
 <LI><A HREF="#Compress">Page Compression</A>
 <LI><A HREF="#CGI">Local CGI</A>
 </UL>
<P>Return to the <A HREF="webview.htm#Contents">Table of Contents...</A>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="Editor"><IMG SRC="../images/rainbowb.gif" 
HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=600 ALT="-----------------------------------------------"></A>

<CENTER><H2>Built-In Text Editor</H2></CENTER>

<P>Webview will let you examine <I>and</I> edit the HTML text of the current page. Just press <B>F9</B> or click the View button near the top right of the form. In text editing mode, you can:
<UL>
<LI>Save, Edit, Find and Print the current text (see the File and Edit menus)
<LI>Create or open another HTML or text document
<LI>View the text as a Web page again (F9 or View button)
<LI>Right-click with the mouse for a quick edit menu
</UL>
<P>Any unsaved changes you make in the text editor will be preserved until you exit Webview, or until you try to edit a different page using F9 or View. You will always be given a chance to save changes before they are discarded.
<P><B>Note:</B> the maximum page size that the Webview text editor can handle is 32 kilobytes.

<P>Return to the <A HREF="#Options">Webview Options...</A>


<P ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="Scripts"><IMG SRC="../images/rainbowb.gif" 
HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=600 ALT="-----------------------------------------------"></A>

<CENTER><H2>Scripted Demonstrations</H2></CENTER>
<P>This option allows you to set up a demonstration of your web pages which will run automatically as soon as Webview starts. It's very useful for shows or other occasions where you want the whole site to be viewed without user involvement. You can choose to let the user intervene by hiding or showing the Pause button, or even running the demonstration in Single Step mode if you like.
<P>Aspects of the display such as the page scrolling and loading rates can be independently controlled. Best of all, you don't need to alter your HTML to make the scripts work!
<P>The best way to learn about scripts is to try one out. Copy the following lines and add them to the end of your Webview.ini file (it's in the same directory as Webview.exe).  Then exit Webview, run it again and watch the results.  Note the pause/play button at the top right of the form -- use this to stop and restart the script any time you like.

<pre>
; Here is a simple script example -- to stop it running automatically whenever
; you load Webview, just put a semicolon in front of the next line:
Script=Sample    ; Which script to run (can define several in the INI file, and use any one)
Page Rate=1      ; milliseconds, i.e. no gap *between* pages
Page Load Delay=2000 ; i.e. wait 2 seconds after load before starting scroll
Scroll Rate=3000 ; millisecs, i.e. 3 seconds between scrolls -- 0 means NO scrolling
Scroll Amount=90 ; % of vertical height of the display area to scroll each step
Pause Button=Yes ; If no, user can't pause the script
Single Step=No   ; If yes, awaits F10 or "play" after each page loads

; Here is the "Sample" script referred to above.
[Sample]
1=alarmrng.wav               ;start a background .wav file
2=webview.htm#Registration  	; Show from the Registration section of Webview.htm onwards
3=SingleStepOn               ; from now on, it is as if SingleStep above had been set to yes
4=webwatch.htm               ; load the page, and then stop (because of SingleStepOn)
5=SingleStepOff              ; back to continuous play
6=wvoptions.htm              ; then show the options page, 
7=Stop                       ; don't start the script again unless F10 or Play is pressed.
</pre>
<p>
The SingleStepOn setting in the [Setups] section can be overridden in the script as above.
<P>Once you've tried that, change to the following display settings. They should give you smooth, continuous scrolling, with a pause at the end of each page:
<pre>
Page Rate=3000   ; 3 second pause at the end of a page
Scroll Rate=100  ; 1/10 second pause between scrolls
Scroll Amount=1  ; scroll by 1% of the display area each time
</pre>

<P>You may also want to experiment by setting <B>Single Step=Yes</B>.
<P>Finally, a few notes on developing scripts using Webview:
<P><UL>
<LI>If you click Play (or push F10) after the script has been paused, it will resume from precisely where it left off, regardless of what other pages you may have manually loaded in the meanwhile.
<LI>If you save changes to a script (e.g. from Notepad) while it is being played, the change will be noticed when the next page is
loaded and the new settings will be adopted. Changes will also be noticed when you Play after pausing the script. In both cases, the script will restart from scratch
<LI>Using the menus while a script is playing will not stop the script, but can conceivably temporarily alter what it is playing
(e.g. the file which is being automatically scrolled will be altered by File|Opening another one).
<LI>If a bad file is referenced in your script, it will automatically pause after showing the error message. Play will continue with the
next line of the script unless you change the script first.
<LI>You can only reference HTML files in a script. If you want to display an image by itself, make a small page with the appropriate IMG SRC tag in it.
</UL>
<P>Return to the <A HREF="#Options">Webview Options...</A>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="Compress"><IMG SRC="../images/rainbowb.gif" 
HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=600 ALT="-----------------------------------------------"></A>

<CENTER><H2>Page Compression -- Speed, Size, Security</H2></CENTER>

<P><I>All</I> copies of Webview 2.5 or later are able to decode and display pages and other files stored in compressed archives.  The process works as follows:

<UL>
<LI>You compress your web pages into an archive using our optional MAKEWV utility, and add a line to the Webview.INI file which tells it the name of your archive
<LI>When Webview is run, it rapidly decompresses the files into a work directory on the user's hard disk. Subsequently, all page display is from hard disk -- much faster than from floppy or CDROM
<LI>Any kind of files -- HTML, images, sound files, CGI applications etc. can be in the archive, but it will still be possible to open or link to other files which are <I>not</I> in the archive
<LI>Pages which came from the archive are protected -- Webview will not let the user view or edit their HTML
<LI>Before Webview exits, the contents of the archive are removed from the user's hard disk
</UL>
<P>Depending on the content of your pages, the amount of space saved will range from 20-50%. GIF and JPG images will hardly compress at all, but HTML, EXE, BMP or WAV files will be significantly compressed. This makes distribution of floppy-based material even easier!
<P>To see a working example of a compressed page archive, make sure you <A HREF="webview.htm#Downloads">download</A> the <I>full</I> evaluation version, then run any of the pages in the Special Features section.
<P>Return to the <A HREF="#Options">Webview Options...</A>


<P ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="CGI"><IMG SRC="../images/rainbowb.gif" 
HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=600 ALT="-----------------------------------------------"></A>

<CENTER><H2>Local CGI</H2></CENTER>
<P>With online web sites, you can write Web applications which process form input and produce result pages which are then sent back to the browser. This is usually done using "Common Gateway Interface" (CGI) calls. <B>Local CGI</B> gives Webview the same capability, except that the crafting of Local CGI applications is usually much easier than the online variety!

<P>You can write your applications in Visual Basic, Borland Delphi, C++ or any programming language which creates executable files.

<P>Just as with regular CGI, a Local CGI call is defined using the &lt;FORM&gt; tag's <B>Method</B> and <B>Action</B> attributes, e.g.<BR>
<pre>        &lt;FORM Method="WVRUN" Action="search.exe srchvals.txt results.htm"&gt;</pre>
<P>The above statement tells Webview that when a button on the form is pressed, it should:
<UL>
<LI>Store the form data in <B>srchvals.txt</B>
<LI>Run the <B>search.exe</B> program with "srchvals.txt" and "results.htm" as parameters
<LI>Wait for search.exe to create a response page in <B>results.htm,</B> then display it 
</UL>

<P>In order to maintain "neutral" behaviour for existing forms you may display, Webview has defined three new <B>Method</B> values:
<UL><LI><B>WVSAVE</B> -- this simply saves the form data in the file specified by the <B>Action</B> attribute, e.g.<BR>
          <pre>        &lt;FORM Method="WVSAVE" Action="order.txt"&gt;</pre>
A message is displayed telling the user where the data has been stored, but no external program is run. Use this for simple no-programming data collection into files in your web page's directory.
<LI><B>WVAPPEND</B> -- this is exactly the same as <B>WVSAVE</B> except that the form information will be <I>appended</I> to the <B>Action</B> file if it already exists
<LI><B>WVRUN</B> -- this will run an external program, with three <B>Action</B> options available, as shown in the examples below:
   <OL><LI>Program name only, e.g.<BR>
<pre>        &lt;FORM Method="WVRUN" Action="notepad.exe"&gt;</pre>
          <BR>This is the same as a direct link to a program -- Webview will run it, but cannot provide it with any form information. The user can return to continue with Webview operations at any time.
           <LI>Program name plus form data filename, e.g. 
          <pre>        &lt;FORM Method="WVRUN" Action="notepad.exe order.txt"&gt;</pre>
           <BR>Webview will first save the form data in <B>order.txt,</B> then call the program with "order.txt" as its only parameter. The program can process that information as it requires. The user can return to continue with Webview operations at any time.
           <LI>Program name, form data filename and result filename, e.g.<BR>
          <pre>        &lt;FORM Method="WVRUN" Action="calcthis.exe rawdata.txt results.htm"&gt;</pre><BR>
           <BR>Webview will:<BR>
           <UL>
              <LI>save the form data to <B>rawdata.txt</B>
              <LI>delete any existing copy of <B>results.htm</B>
              <LI>execute the program with "rawdata.txt" and "results.htm" as parameters
              <LI><I>wait</I> until the result file has been created <B>and</B> closed by the program
              <LI>load <B>result.htm</B> and display it as an HTML file (regardless of its extension)
          </UL>
          <P>Note that if the result file hasn't been created by the program within 10 seconds, Webview will display an error message and stop waiting. The 10 second default can be altered to, say, 30 seconds by adding a "Wait For CGI=30" line to the [Setups] section of Webview.ini.
   </OL>
</UL>

<H3>Where files are located when using Local CGI</H3>

<P>EXE files referenced in <B>Action</B> statements (and also in direct HREF links) are assumed to be: 
<OL><LI>in the specified path if an absolute path is given
<LI>in or relative to the current web page's directory, if present
<LI>otherwise assumed to be on the system path
</OL>
<P>Form data and result page files referenced in <B>Action</B> statements are located as follows
<OL><LI>in the specified path if an absolute path is given
<LI>if "CDROM=Yes" is  in the [Setups] section of Webview.ini, in the system's TEMP (if defined) or Windows directory
<LI>otherwise in or relative to the current web page's directory
</OL>
<P>Regardless of where the files end up, the <I>correct</I> path is always passed to the program, so it simply needs to use the path(s) which Webview will specify in the parameter list, e.g.<BR> <B>myapp.exe c:\temp\formdata.txt c:\temp\output.htm</B>

<P>Now you know how to call your Local CGI program, you simply need to write the code to process the form data file (test-drive our <B>Order form</B> in the <A HREF="webview.htm#Downloads">evaluation version</A> to see an example of one such file). Then, if necessary, have the program  generate an HTML response page. Have fun!
<P>Return to the <A HREF="#Options">Webview Options...</A>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/rainbowb.gif" 
HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=600 ALT="-----------------------------------------------">

<P>
<table border=3>
<tr>
   <td><IMG SRC="/images/letters.gif"><A HREF="mailto:peter@spis.co.nz">Mail Peter</A></td>
   <td><A HREF="../index.htm">SPIS home page</A></td>
